<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ind. Town Residents: Racism Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- The killing of a Korean student by a  
white supremacist blamed for a two-state rampage against minorities 
was a shock to what many see as a welcoming college town, a place 
of quirky bookstores, Big Ten athletics and intellectual residents. 
</P>
<P>
	But some residents say there are really two Bloomingtons: the  
liberal community attached to Indiana University, whose campus 
occupies much of the city, and another town more typical of the 
conservative, white-dominated state where it's located. 
</P>
<P>
	``For anyone who is not white, it was not a surprise,'' said  
Suzanne Faulk, a 48-year-old black Bloomington native and secretary 
at the city's biggest black church. ``It was a surprise it hadn't 
happened before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is sometimes called the most northern Southern state, and  
``race has always been a challenge in Indiana,'' said James 
Madison, an IU history professor. 
</P>
<P>
	The white supremacist, Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, is believed to  
have gone on a three-day crime wave through Illinois and Indiana 
that targeted blacks, Jews and Asians. Two people were killed -- a 
black man in the Chicago suburb of Skokie and the Korean student in 
Bloomington -- and nine others were injured. On July 4, Smith 
apparently committed suicide following a police chase. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people on the university campus were already familiar with  
Smith, a former English and criminal-justice student who openly 
espoused white supremacist views and passed out leaflets. 
</P>
<P>
	On one occasion, more than 500 people marched along  
Bloomington's tree-lined streets protesting Smith's leaflets and 
views. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloomington, about 60 miles southwest of Indianapolis, is more  
than 90 percent white. Four percent of its residents are black and 
5 percent are members of other non-white groups. 
</P>
<P>
	And it sits in the middle of a state where blacks and other  
minorities comprise only about 9 percent of the population, a state 
that has long been fertile ground for the Ku Klux Klan. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana became a stronghold for the Klan in the 1920s, when the  
biggest Klan rally on record drew nearly 200,000 people to the 
north-central city of Kokomo. 
</P>
<P>
	``People in Indiana have not had as much experience living with  
'others,''' Madison said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Bloomington residents say their city of 65,000 is different  
from the rest of the state. For one thing, the Big Ten school draws 
about a third of its 35,000 students from outside Indiana and about 
16 percent of its students are not white. 
</P>
<P>
	IU's music department is ranked second in the nation. An  
Internet magazine recently ranked the campus second on a list of 
the most ``wired'' public universities in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the most wonderful places in the U.S.,'' said  
Patrick Efiom, a black social worker and a former IU student. 
</P>
<P>
	But other black residents -- mostly those with few ties to the  
university -- say they see racial intimidation often enough to 
consider the insults part of their everyday lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't happen in one part of town or another,'' said  
Faulk. ``It's all over, all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the more visible signs, many residents say, is a parking  
area near the town square, where small crowds park their pickups 
and party on most weekend nights. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not uncommon to see Confederate flags there -- on bumper  
stickers, car-seat covers or waving in the breeze -- and several 
blacks report regularly hearing racial insults as they pass by. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't do anything about it because it happens all the  
time,'' said Kenya James, a 17-year-old high school junior who used 
to work at a Taco Bell across the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say they haven't received any race-related complaints  
about the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlie Nelms, who is black and the university's vice president  
for student development and diversity, said Bloomington is not 
unlike any other place he's ever lived. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are divided according to social class and race,'' like  
most every place else in America, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bloomington is America,'' Madison said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
