<DOCNO> APW19990710.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 08:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Chiefs Want More Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a decade of shrinking the military, the  
nation's uniformed chiefs are beginning to call for an about-face. 
The post-Cold War world, they argue, is putting a bigger strain on 
America's armed forces than the Clinton administration and Congress 
-- even the military -- had imagined. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking beyond lessons learned from the strains of fighting a  
78-day air war in Yugoslavia, the Navy is eyeing more ships and 
sailors and the Air Force more planes and pilots. The Army and 
Marine Corps, whose leaders took over just a few weeks ago, are 
studying the matter but may also want more. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy is the most outspoken.  
</P>
<P>
	``We must reverse our current downsizing trajectory,'' Adm. Jay  
Johnson, the chief of naval operations, said in a recent speech. He 
cited ``mounting evidence'' that the future fleet of 305 ships the 
Navy once thought would be enough -- there are 322 today -- ``is not 
likely to be enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. military has no match today, but is stretched thin,  
even in peace. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have found that peacetime is not what it used to be,'' Rep.  
Ike Skelton, D-Mo., said in a recent speech on the House floor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps are about one-third  
smaller than at the end of the Cold War in 1989, yet Skelton says 
their pace of operations, in war and in peace, is 300 percent 
faster. 
</P>
<P>
	The result: overworked troops, shortages of spare parts and  
aircraft and other weapons not ready for war. This has made it 
harder for the services to retain their best people, many of whom 
can make more money as civilians. The Air Force, for example, has 
an especially big problem keeping pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said the problem is particularly acute for those forces  
not first in line to deploy abroad, in the Navy's case the ship and 
aircraft crews at home bases training for their next missions. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're still expected to go here, train there, do this, do  
that; you don't have the people, you don't have the parts, you 
don't have the money, and you're just spinning yourself in. That's 
what's killing us,'' Johnson said in an interview in his Pentagon 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	The military has known for several years that overseas  
commitments -- from peacekeeping in Bosnia to combat air patrols 
over Iraq, from threats of war in Korea to an air campaign in 
Yugoslavia, and now a long-term peacekeeping mission in Kosovo -- 
were straining its resources. 
</P>
<P>
	What's different now is that some are making the case for a  
bigger military, a reversal of the ``downsizing'' trend that began 
in the mid-1980s and continued through the Pentagon's most recent 
assessment of the nation's defense needs. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1997 Pentagon study concluded the active-duty military could  
be cut to 1.36 million troops at the start of the 21st century 
without undue risk of undermining the nation's security. That 
compares with 2.13 million when the Berlin Wall fell in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was based in part on a judgment that the biggest  
threat facing the United States was ``coercion and large-scale, 
cross-border aggression against U.S. allies'' by hostile states 
with significant military power, such as Iran, Iraq and North 
Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	While those threats have not disappeared, the biggest drain on  
the U.S. military in recent years has been the air war over 
Yugoslavia, which severely stretched the Air Force and forced the 
Navy to divert an aircraft carrier from East Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has been eager to provide more money for the military,  
including a 4.8 percent pay raise in the budget year starting Oct. 
1, which is more than President Clinton had proposed. Increasing 
the size of the military may be harder, despite early support from 
some key lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of Congress will press the military to trim its  
headquarters staffs, which many consider bloated, and to make more 
use of private contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	Skelton, ranking Democrat on the House Armed Services Committee,  
is particularly worried about the Army. 
</P>
<P>
	``To put it bluntly,'' Skelton said, ``the Army today is too  
small.'' It may need an extra 40,000 soldiers to meet its worldwide 
commitments without wearing out its people and weapons, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Eric Shinseki, speaking to reporters June 23, a day after  
he took +ver as Army chief of staff, said he needed time to study 
the issue but his gut feeling told him an Army of 480,000 soldiers, 
the limit set by Congress, is too small. He said he would know more 
precisely in a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	In a departure interview last month with the Marine Corps Times  
newspaper, Gen. Charles Krulak, the Marine Corps commandant, said 
his service needs about 5,000 more troops. ``We have cut past the 
fat, cut past the muscle, and we're into the bone,'' the newspaper 
quoted Krulak as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Krulak's successor, Gen. Jim Jones, said at his Senate  
confirmation hearing in June that the Marines have cut back so far 
they lost a ``shock absorber'' of force strength. He said a study 
begun during Krulak's tenure was looking at troop totals and all 
other aspects of the Marines' force structure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I predict that one of the findings will be that we would like  
to have the shock absorber back,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force, now catching its breath after the Kosovo bombing  
campaign, is studying the implications of that 11-week war, both in 
future needs for more planes and ``in terms of the total number of 
people'' it needs, a senior Air Force officer told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The officer, who discussed the matter on condition he not be  
identified, said that in organizing a new system of 10 air 
expeditionary forces for overseas contingencies, planners 
discovered they are 3,000 people short. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
