<DOCNO> APW19990710.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 08:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gephardt Withdraws Muslim Nominee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt has  
withdrawn his appointment of a Muslim leader to a congressional 
panel assigned to review U.S. policy on terrorism. Jewish groups 
and several members of Congress said the nominee had justified acts 
of terror against Israel and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., Gephardt  
said Salam Al-Marayati, director of the Muslim Public Affairs 
Council in Los Angeles, had been recommended to him as having 
extensive public service experience and being involved in 
interfaith dialogue. 
</P>
<P>
	The Missouri Democrat said, however, the appointment was  
subsequently questioned and since a security check could take a 
year, twice as long as the life of the commission, he was 
withdrawing the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite these circumstances, Mr. Al-Marayati is prepared to  
provide input to the commission on matters of interest and concern 
to the American Muslim community,'' Gephardt said in the letter, 
obtained by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt told Hastert he hoped the panel would ``listen to the  
voices of this community and address the issues of civil rights for 
all Americans consistent with a strong U.S. anti-terrorism 
policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seven House members wrote FBI Director Louis Freeh they had  
received information of statements by Al-Marayati justifying 
terrorism against Israel and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``These assertions cause us great concern as it is essential  
that all members of the commission be unequivocally committed to 
the prevention and prosecution of terrorism directed at the United 
States or our ally Israel,'' they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment had been challenged by the Zionist Organization  
of America, the American Jewish Congress, the Anti-Defamation 
League and by the American Jewish Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	David A. Harris, executive director of the American Jewish  
Committee, said Al-Marayati for a number of years had justified and 
minimized acts of terrorism against Israel and against the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Morton A, Klein, national director of the Zionist Organization  
of America, said in a statement that ``these anti-Israel and 
pro-terrorist individuals and groups should be condemned and 
relegated to the margins of society, not granted credibility by 
being given government appointments and meetings at the White 
House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Council on American-Islamic Relations denounced Gephardt's  
decision and said he had bowed to political pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	``This reversal by Representative Gephardt will only serve to  
institutionalize discrimination against American Muslims and their 
leaders,'' the council said in a statement. ``Muslims have been 
widely stereotyped using the issue of terrorism and it is therefore 
essential that a credible Muslim voice be heard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Muslim Public Affairs Council called on Hastert and Gephardt  
to reinstate their director ``and allow the country to hear a 
Muslim voice'' on the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	It accused the ``pro-Israel lobby'' of manipulating discussion  
of an important issue, and said the Jewish groups that oppsoed 
Al-Marayati were ``extreme Zionist organizations'' trying to 
establish a pro-Israel litmus test for any Muslim considered for 
national service. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Marayati told The New York Times he would not withdraw. ``I  
think that if there is a political will, there is a way to expedite 
these security clearances and get down to the business of the 
country,'' he was quoted as saying. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
