<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Returning to Newark, N.J. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- In the 1930s and '40s, it was hard to  
imagine a more baseball-crazy place than Newark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newark Bears were the nation's top minor league team,  
regularly cranking out new players for the powerhouse New York 
Yankees. The Newark Eagles, a top-flight Negro League team, 
featured five future Hall of Famers. Team rosters included such 
greats as Yogi Berra, Monte Irvin and Larry Doby. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans celebrated the Bears' return from spring training in  
Florida with an annual parade through the city. When other Negro 
League teams were scheduled for home games with the visiting 
Eagles, they commonly switched the games to Newark because Eagles 
fans could be counted on to pack the stands. Lena Horne and Joe 
Louis caught most Eagles openers. 
</P>
<P>
	But all that faded when both teams quit the city after the 1949  
season, leaving 14,000-seat Ruppert Stadium, which they shared, an 
empty curiosity until it was torn down in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Next Friday, professional baseball returns to Newark when the  
new Newark Bears, a franchise of the independent Atlantic League, 
christen the 6,014-seat Riverfront Stadium -- at $34 million one of 
the most expensive minor league ballparks ever built. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's return is being hailed both by fans eager to revive a  
storied sporting tradition and by politicians hoping to replace 
negative images of a city still struggling to recover from race 
riots in the late 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Newark has always been a hotbed for baseball for as long as I  
can remember,'' says Irvin, the Hall of Fame outfielder who starred 
with the Eagles in the 1940s before helping lead the New York 
Giants to pennants in 1951 and 1954. 
</P>
<P>
	``I go way back to the Knothole Gang,'' he says, recalling the  
program that allowed thousands of youngsters to see Bears games 
from the bleachers at reduced prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I became a member of the Newark Eagles, and we won our  
first championship in 1946. It was a very happy time in my life. It 
was a real pleasure playing in Newark. Every Tuesday they'd have 
Ladies Night and on Sundays people would come straight from church 
in their coats and ties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doby, who played two seasons for the Eagles, was the second  
black player in the major leagues, joining the Cleveland Indians in 
1947 a few weeks after Jackie Robinson signed with the Brooklyn 
Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Doby recalls the segregation of the time, noting that the Bears  
stayed at the Riviera Hotel on High Street, which had a white 
clientele, and the Eagles stayed at the black-owned Grand Hotel on 
West Market. He says black players patronized the city's 
black-owned establishments. ``They knew we played for the Newark 
Eagles and treated us with great respect,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Indians, Doby had to eat and sleep apart from his  
teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't as comfortable as playing in Newark,'' he recalls.  
``There, you knew you could be together with your teammates in the 
same hotels, restaurants and buses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1946, Berra tore up the International League, lacing pitches  
thrown over his head or down in the dirt for base hits in 77 games 
with the Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good baseball town,'' says Berra, the catcher who  
went on to anchor Yankee dynasty teams of the 1950s and '60s. ``I 
loved it here; it was great. We had a lot of fun in Newark, we 
really did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, suddenly, it was over. The Eagles, tangled in the decline  
of the Negro League after baseball's color line was broken, moved 
to Houston. The Bears were sold to the Chicago Cubs and moved to 
Springfield, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Sharpe James says the dual departures tore a hole in  
Newark's civic fabric. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took away an image that the city could clearly identify  
with, something we could worship and talk about. We didn't have 
anything that belonged to everyone in Newark anymore,'' he says. 
``It was a rallying point for the whole community, something to 
talk about and brag about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team that now carries the Bears name is owned by another  
former Yankee catcher, Rick Cerone, a hometown boy who has invested 
more than $2 million in the fledgling franchise. The new Bears, 
created last year, have played 121 games, both ``home'' and away, 
on the road over two seasons, waiting for completion of the new 
ballpark downtown along the Passaic River. 
</P>
<P>
	As young Rick was learning the game on the city's sandlots, his  
father, Aldo, passed along stories of sneaking into Ruppert Stadium 
as a kid. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wanted me to know that where we grew up was a place that  
had a great history of professional baseball,'' Cerone says. ``I 
had offers to go to other cities that were going to do this and 
that for us, but this is kind of personal. I didn't want to give up 
on Newark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The baseball venture is not without critics. Cost overruns  
doubled the stadium's estimated cost. The city and Essex County are 
footing the bill, hoping to recoup some of the money under a 
complicated revenue-sharing arrangement with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Others question the economic impact a minor league baseball  
stadium can have on Newark's downtown; one economist has likened it 
to the opening of a supermarket. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears hope to draw about 120,000 fans for its 36 games at  
Riverfront Stadium this year. Opening night is sold out. The team 
aims to provide affordable nights out for families (ticket prices 
range from $6 to $8) and a place where former big leaguers looking 
for second chances or hopeful kids can catch the eyes of major 
league scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerone has taken pains to incorporate Newark baseball history. A  
picnic area in left field is called the Eagles' Nest and the team 
mascot is named ``Rippin' Ruppert.'' He says he'll revive the 
Knothole Gang tradition by bringing area schoolkids into the park 
at cut-rate prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``This city is going to be special again,'' Cerone says. ``If  
this makes people proud to have the word `Newark' on the front of 
their chest again, then it'll all be worth it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
