<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Celebrates 90th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP is recommitting itself to fight ills  
still gripping black America as the nation's largest and oldest 
civil rights organization celebrates its 90th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This convention will be celebratory, but we will also be  
looking back towards the principles we were founded on,'' said 
Julian Bond, the NAACP's national board chairman. ``It's nice to 
reminisce, but we can't afford not to keep looking forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an expected 14,000 members trickled into New York for  
Saturday's start of the six-day conference, NAACP officials mourned 
Friday's death of James Farmer, founder of the Congress of Racial 
Equality and the last survivor of the ``Big Four'' who guided the 
civil rights battles of the 1950s and 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	``The civil rights movement has lost a giant,'' Bond said.  
</P>
<P>
	The four -- Farmer, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. of the Southern  
Christian Leadership Conference, Whitney Young of the Urban League 
and Roy Wilkins of the NAACP -- led many of the marches, sit-ins and 
freedom rides through the South that transformed America's racial 
landscape. 
</P>
<P>
	While those accomplishments helped in the area of public  
accommodations and voting rights, the civil rights struggles of the 
1990s are examining why black Americans are paid less, do not 
achieve as well in school and vote in fewer numbers than whites. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to look inward first as a community looking for  
solutions,'' said the NAACP's president, Kweisi Mfume, who is 
responsible for day-to-day operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel we have strengths we don't always use. Once we look  
inside to overcome obstacles, then we can pressure government and 
others to our causes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The convention's wide-ranging agenda also deals with police  
brutality, job discrimination in federal workplaces, health 
disparities between white and black America and peace and order in 
Africa, Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was heartened that a major part of the NAACP program,  
economic development in poor areas, received a presidential embrace 
last week. President Clinton toured areas like the Watts 
neighborhood in Los Angeles with corporate leaders, spreading a 
message for increased private investment and government incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good first step, but it has to be followed by  
substance,'' Mfume said. ``This president has reached out before, 
but he has to have a Congress that shares those same goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also expected to draw attention at the convention, which closes  
Thursday, is the March increase in annual dues from $10 to $30. 
Some worry it could hurt the struggling smaller branches among the 
2,220 in the NAACP. 
</P>
<P>
	For much of the year, it seemed the 90th birthday party for the  
NAACP would double as a going away party for Mfume, a former 
five-term congressman from Baltimore, where the NAACP is 
headquartered. Influential city leaders there had courted Mfume to 
run for mayor, and many political observers said Mfume likely would 
cruise to victory. But in May, he decided not to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that my job is to finish the work I have begun here,''  
Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond added the group needs stable leadership after recent years  
of power fights and squabbling at the top. 
</P>
<P>
	``As an organization, we badly need consistency,'' Bond said.  
``We are relieved he's going to stay with us, and we won't have to 
go through the torturous process of having to replace him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
