<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steels' Stage Victory Taken Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAUBEUGE, France (AP) -- Tom Steels already won two stages at the  
Tour de France, and he dearly wanted to win the one at Maubeuge, so 
close to his home country of Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Steels who crossed the finish line first in Friday's  
sixth stage, but he watched rival sprinter Mario Cipollini of Italy 
get the glory. The jury ruled that Steels unfairly swerved out of 
his line of motion and impeded the movement of another rider. 
</P>
<P>
	Cipollini, known as the ``Lion King'' and the ``King of  
Sprints,'' will be remembered for a rare hat trick. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time a rider won three consecutive stages of the Tour  
de France was 1948 when Gino Bartali, another Italian, did it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This annulment was justified, because we almost had a serious  
accident,'' said Cipollini, who is in second place. ``The sprint 
must be correct. The rules are clear. Steels was in a line, then he 
passed three meters to the right at the moment (Jan) Svorada was 
passing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was not Steels' first incident with Tour de France  
authorities. In 1997, he was thrown out of the Tour after hurling a 
water bottle at another rider during a sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	If Steels' victory was clean, he would have finished the day  
only three seconds behind the overall leader, Jaan Kirsipuu of 
Estonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Erik Zabel moved up to second in the stage and Jaan  
Kirsipuu of Estonia was third -- enough to hold onto the coveted 
yellow jersey by 26 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Steels was awarded 172nd place in the stage -- fifth from last  
place. He remains third in the overall standings. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's Stuart O'Grady is fourth in the overall standings,  
followed by Zabel. American Lance Armstrong, coming back from 
testicular cancer, is in sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Every stage this week has been marked by unsuccessful early  
breakaways followed by a furious sprint to the finish line. 
Friday's stage was no exception. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the longest breakaway was led by Francois Simon, the  
French national champion, who was trying to win a Tour de France 
stage as did each of his older brothers: Pascal, Regis and Jerome. 
</P>
<P>
	But Simon's group was caught by the pack at 5 miles before the  
end. 
</P>
<P>
	The 107-mile route began at Amiens in the Somme region, where  
the famous World War I battle was fought. War cemeteries remain 
today, including some for Australian and British soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	The riders passed fields of potatoes and sugar beets as the  
route headed to Maubeuge, just near Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen riders broke out at after 4 miles from the starting  
point of Amiens, a city known for having the largest cathedral in 
France. But they were soon swallowed by the pack. 
</P>
<P>
	The second breakaway came at about 16 miles and featured 18  
riders. Among them were Armstrong and Tyler Hamilton. But the 
Americans were caught 9 miles later. 
</P>
<P>
	The main breakaway came after 46 miles, when Simon and fellow  
Frenchmen Frederic Guesdon and Gilles Maignan broke loose, as did 
Francisco Cerezo of Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	But the four, like so many before them this week, were unable to  
stay ahead of the pack and the final onslaught of sprinters. 
</P>
<P>
	When the race hits the mountains next week, the sprinters will  
give way to the climbing specialists, and many may drop out. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
