<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 20:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Bradley Highlights Race Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the city where his professional basketball  
legend was crafted, Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley 
told thousands of NAACP delegates Saturday night that matters of 
racial justice would get top priority in his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, race is the reason I'm in politics,'' Bradley  
said in brief comments to a gathering of 3,500 at a gospel show to 
start the NAACP's 90th annual convention. Bradley, a former New 
Jersey senator, explained that watching the discussion and 
successful vote on the 1964 civil rights bill helped push him 
towards a life of political service. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, the lone candidate facing Vice President Al Gore in the  
Democratic field, said that while blacks are advancing in some 
quarters like home ownership rates, 40 percent of black children 
live in poverty, compared to 20 percent of all children. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I become president, I promise those numbers will go down in  
my time in office,'' Bradley said to applause from the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that he would strengthen hate-crime legislation,  
support affirmative action laws and appoint people ``who reflect 
the talent in the African American community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's visit to the nation's largest civil rights group was  
somewhat unexpected. He wasn't listed on the program and NAACP 
officials expressed doubts as late as noon Saturday that Bradley 
would be able to attend. They could confirm Bradley's appearance 
only hours before the gospel show started. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore raised more than $18 million through June 30, Bradley  
took in a respectable sum of more than $11 million. His 
fund-raising efforts have been aided by prominent sports figures 
like Los Angeles Lakers Coach Phil Jackson, who roomed with Bradley 
while playing for the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore enjoys several advantages over Bradley, including a greater  
number of political endorsements and the platform of the White 
House. And a June CNN-Gallup-USA Today survey gave Gore a 64 
percent to 28 percent lead. The survey had a plus or minus 5 
percentage point margin of error. 
</P>
<P>
	But appealing to the black vote in 2000 may be an area of  
Bradley strength. Bettering race relations was one of Bradley's 
reoccurring themes during his 18 years as New Jersey senator. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Bradley termed racial unity as ``the defining moral  
issue of our time'' and set the pursuit of social integration at 
the top of his presidential campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 12:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Education Is Top US Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told the country's  
second largest teachers' union Saturday he would ``move heaven and 
earth'' to make education the top U.S. priority. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore did not mention the 2000 presidential race directly in a  
speech at the national meeting of the American Federation of 
Teachers. But he said that in any ``future public service,'' issues 
such as more money to repair crumbling and overcrowded schools, 
improve classroom technology and increase teacher pay would top his 
agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to have a national commitment that education is our  
No. 1 priority,'' Gore told about 2,000 cheering teachers. ``I will 
move heaven and earth, and leave no stone unturned, to bring about 
the revolutionary change we need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has asked Congress for tax breaks that would  
free up $25 billion in private money for school modernization 
targeted at poor inner-city schools. Gore said poorly maintained 
schools help create indifferent students. 
</P>
<P>
	``The powerful but unspoken message: if you want to goof off, if  
you think you education is not that important to you, go right 
ahead. It's not that important to us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But repairing schools shows a ``commitment'' that the primary  
goal is learning, Gore said, sending a new message to students: 
``You ought to do your part and study hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans in Congress also advocate tax incentives to raise  
more money for public school construction, but their plan does not 
set aside money specifically for inner-city districts. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing federal budget surplus projections, Gore said education  
priorities should include hiring more teachers to reduce 
overcrowding, paying them more, and ensuring the Internet becomes 
more fully integrated in classroom teaching. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke with pride of the ``e-rate'' -- Republicans call it the  
``Gore tax'' -- a telephone fee he pushed that has raised $2 billion 
for classroom Internet hookups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to have them name it after me,'' he said. ``We have  
to finish the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teachers applauded enthusiastically throughout Gore's  
speech, but afterwards some said they want to see the words backed 
up with actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody talks about how important education is, but when it  
gets right down to it, where's the money?'' said Lyris Russ, a Los 
Angeles elementary school teacher with 27 years' experience. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 09:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Comeback Welcome, Reassuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- From old-fashioned semiconductor makers to  
newfangled Internet companies, the high-tech businesses that 
dominate the Nasdaq composite index are on a roll. They propelled 
the index to six new records over the course of seven recent 
trading sessions, and show no signs of flagging. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Nasdaq rose 21.21 to close at 2,793.07, a modest  
gain, but enough to lock in the latest record high close. The 
index, as important as the Dow Jones industrials to many investors, 
has tumbled and soared over the past year, but this past week's 
broad-based advance offered welcome reassurance that despite the 
youth of many of its companies, the Nasdaq remains strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Records are being set and smashed with stunning frequency in the  
continuing bull market, but the Nasdaq's gains are noteworthy 
nonetheless, for in the two months leading up to the streak, the 
index saw some dark moments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq struggled through much of May and June as investors  
moved their money away from technology shares and toward more 
conservative investments. The culprit? The threat of higher 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-growth, often high-priced technology companies that  
often feed the Nasdaq's growth faltered as the Federal Reserve 
debated whether to raise rates. Higher rates can endanger any stock 
by boosting the cost of borrowing and cutting into corporate 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the technology companies that may post meager earnings on  
the promise of future growth are especially vulnerable, said Hugh 
Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``When interest rates are high, I'm less likely to take a chance  
on a company that promises me results someday'' rather than now, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed ended the suspense June 30, raising interest rates a  
modest quarter-percentage point. And then a funny thing happened: 
Companies began dropping hints about their second-quarter earnings, 
and high-tech companies were able to entice investors by indicating 
they actually could deliver good results right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're through the preannouncements, and we got through with  
relatively few blowups,'' said Curt Rohrman, a fund manager and 
assistant vice president at USA Imco Equity Investments in San 
Antonio. ``The quarterly numbers should be very good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! offered confirmation this past week, announcing it had  
earned 11 cents per share in the second quarter, above the 8 cents 
per share forecast by First Call Corp., and even surpassing the 
rumored 9 or 10 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock did slip a bit, as investors locked in profits after  
bidding it higher in the days leading up to the announcement. But 
Yahoo! has clearly helped the Nasdaq's gains, rising from 120 in 
early June to a peak of 178 1/8 July 2. 
</P>
<P>
	That high price illustrates one of the ironies of the Nasdaq.  
The index, which traditionally listed the smallest and youngest of 
the publicly traded companies has seen many fledgling firms balloon 
in size. Some have moved to the New York Stock Exchange in search 
of a higher profile, but high-tech powerhouses like Microsoft and 
Intel still trade through Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	Those industry leaders are driving the recent runup, Johnson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've had very good relative performance, right across the  
board,'' he said, pointing to semiconductor makers like Intel, 
networking companies like Cisco Systems and Internet retailers like 
Amazon.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell joined the high-tech celebration Friday as Goldman, Sachs &AMP;  
Co. added the company, the nation's largest direct seller of 
personal computers, to its list of recommended stocks for private 
clients. 
</P>
<P>
	The breadth of the recent gains heartens analysts, who last year  
bemoaned the soaring valuations of Internet stocks that showed few 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry is maturing,'' Johnson said. ``Investors are now  
gravitating toward companies where there's a good chance the 
earnings will be better than estimates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq ended the week with a gain of 52.05 points, or 1.9  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow industrials average set a record of its own Friday,  
rising 66.81 points to close at 11,193.70. The blue-chip index rose 
54.46 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 12.06 for the week, picking  
up 8.86 Friday to close at 1,403.28, also a record. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Stock Exchange composite was up 2.56 for the week,  
rising 3.63 Friday to 657.68. The American Stock Exchange composite 
picked up 10.31 on the week and closed at 812.73, rising 4.04 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index, reflecting the performance of  
small-company stocks, inched up 1.47 for the week to 457.98, having 
risen 3.23 Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wilshire Associates Equity Index -- which represents the  
combined market value of all NYSE, American and Nasdaq issues -- 
ended the week at $12.84 trillion, up $102.56 billion from last 
week. A year ago, the index was $10.88 trillion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
