<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chi. Cop Shooting Found Unjustified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Police Department's Office of Professional  
Standards says the shooting of a passenger in a car that had fled 
police was not justified and that the four officers involved should 
be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Superintendent Terry Hillard will consider the  
recommendations over the weekend, a police spokesman said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	After a short police chase, LaTanya Haggerty, 26, was shot and  
killed June 4 when an officer mistook her cellular phone for a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	In Haggerty's case and that of another police shooting on June  
5, both the victims and the officers who fired were black. The 
cases have raised questions about how the race of suspects may be a 
factor in tense situations, even when the officers themselves are 
black. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers were wrong to fire at the car and they disobeyed orders  
to break off the chase, according to the report given to Hillard on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hillard will decide whether to forward the panel's findings to  
the police board, or he can recommend up to a 30-day suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope he (Hillard) doesn't succumb to public pressure and he  
does what's right,'' said Bill Nolan of the Fraternal Order of 
Police. ``If that is not the case we'll make our voices known.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The police group plans protests if Hillard suggests anything  
more than a suspension, Nolan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook County State's Attorney Dick Devine has not decided whether  
to press criminal charges against the officers, said spokesman Bob 
Benjamin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
