<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's World Cup Making History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- It was not the biggest game in the lives  
of several American soccer players. Just the latest biggest one for 
the likes of Kristine Lilly, Michelle Akers, Mia Hamm and Julie 
Foudy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, the Women's World Cup grabbed headlines and the  
imagination of the country. Yes, as many as 90,000 fans were in the 
Rose Bowl for today's final against China. Certainly, what they had 
done over the last three weeks was a monumental achievement for 
themselves, their sport, their gender and their gender's sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, that foursome has been through a lot since joining the  
national team. And they just might go through a lot more, such as 
at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long road and a memorable one,'' said Akers, at 33  
the oldest U.S. player. She joined the national squad in 1985 and 
is one of the best the sport has produced. ``This tournament has 
been wonderful for what it has done for women's sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some great times before, though.''  
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Akers was the mainstay of the 1991 team that won the  
first Women's World Cup. She led the tournament in scoring as a 
striker, but since has moved back to midfield, where she controls 
the pace and distributes the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Akers played in only two Cup games because of injury.  
She also struggled through the 1996 Olympics, physically exhausted 
at the end, but still playing a key role in capturing the gold 
medal. She then was diagnosed with chronic fatigue syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	So Akers has had lots of battles in her career.  
</P>
<P>
	Hamm, who entered today's game with a tender left hamstring,  
came aboard in 1987. She is the career goals leader, men or women, 
in international play. Through two World Cups, an Olympics and 
Goodwill Games, she has been the focal point of the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	All of that experience made it easier for Hamm to handle the  
hype and pressure associated with the championship match. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think if we win or lose will have that much of an  
impact, because this tournament has been a tremendous success 
already,'' Hamm said Friday. ``And this team has been able to bring 
about a lot of excitement and recognition for women's sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I think people also realized how well the other teams play  
and how entertaining our game is. The World Cup has achieved what 
all of us wanted it to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foudy, a co-captain and one of the most spirited of players,  
first played for the national team in 1988. She has been at the 
core of just about every major achievement the Americans have 
managed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been everything we dreamed or imagined it would be,''  
she said of the tournament. ``But it isn't the first time we've 
played under pressure and gone after a huge prize. We've had our 
share of big games, and we've done pretty well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly, like Foudy and Akers, is a midfielder who also began  
playing for the U.S. team in '87. She's been a forward, too, and a 
true sparkplug. 
</P>
<P>
	As she surveyed the scene over the past three weeks, Lilly  
couldn't help but think back to the early days. 
</P>
<P>
	``People don't realize what you had to do to be on this national  
team back then,'' Lilly said. ``We had to train by ourselves 
because there wasn't a team to play with. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the thing that set apart the national team players  
from the ones who didn't make it was the great commitment they had 
on their own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A commitment that shows no signs of disappearing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
