<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comparison of Tax Relief Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A comparison of differing draft tax relief bills proposed by key  
Republicans in the House and Senate. Both would cut taxes using 
projected budget surpluses over the next 10 years. 

</P>
<P>
                              *HOUSE   	
</P>
<P>
	--Total cost: estimated $864 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	--Cut income tax rates 10 percent across the board over a decade.  
</P>
<P>
	--Reduce the top tax rate on long-term capital gains from 20  
percent to 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gradually phase out estate taxes..  
</P>
<P>
	--Create education IRA for public and private elementary and  
secondary schools. 
</P>
<P>
	--Tax-free prepaid tuition accounts for private universities.  
</P>
<P>
	--Add personal exemption for long-term care of an elderly  
relative. 
</P>
<P>
	--Unspecified relief from ``marriage penalty'' that affects  
two-income couples. 
</P>
<P>
	--Possible phaseout of alternative minimum tax for individuals.  

</P>
<P>
                              *SENATE   	
</P>
<P>
	--Total cost: estimated $792 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	--Reduce bottom income tax bracket from 15 percent to 14 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	--Eliminate ``marriage penalty'' by allowing married couples to  
file joint returns as if single. 
</P>
<P>
	--Permanently exclude personal credits from triggering  
alternative minimum tax. 
</P>
<P>
	--Raise to $5,000 the limit on contributions to individual  
retirement accounts and eliminate all limits on income for making 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Create a new Roth 401(k) plan in which employees could  
contribute after-tax dollars that would then be tax-free upon 
withdrawal. Similar to popular Roth IRA. 
</P>
<P>
	--Raise by 50 percent the limits on contributions to all 401(k)  
and 403(b) plans. 
</P>
<P>
	--Tax-free prepaid tuition plans for private higher education.  
</P>
<P>
	--Raise to 50 percent the child care expenses that can be  
deducted from income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Make health insurance fully tax deductible for people not  
covered by employer-subsidized plans. 
</P>
<P>
	--An additional tax exemption for people who take care of elderly  
family members. 
</P>
<P>
	--Unspecified relief from estate tax.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
