<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 00:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Source: Sen. Smith Leaving GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Critics of Sen. Bob Smith's expected  
decision to quit the Republican Party say he is killing two birds 
with one stone -- his presidential campaign and re-election to his 
Senate seat. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Hampshire conservative is prepared to announce next week  
that he will leave the GOP and continue his campaign for the 
presidency as an independent or third-party candidate, a source 
close to the campaign said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith plans to bolt the party not because of his campaign, which  
has garnered little support, but because of his philosophical 
objection to the direction of the Republican mainstream, said the 
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith has threatened to quit several times in recent weeks,  
contending that many Republicans have abandoned their conservative 
base by softening their positions against abortion and gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republican National Chairman Jim Nicholson said it was the  
other way around. 
</P>
<P>
	``This would not be a case of the party leaving you, Bob, but  
rather of you leaving our party,'' he said in a letter to Smith. He 
called such a decision a ``serious mistake for you personally, with 
only a marginal political impact -- and a counterproductive one at 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Duprey, the state Republican chairman, added: ``This is a  
selfish move and is doomed to failure. It signals the end of his 
political career in New Hampshire. Bob should not seek the 
nomination of our party in 2002 for the Senate if he is unwilling 
to stay in our party now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The source said Smith was talking to GOP leaders, friends and  
supporters about leaving the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican state Rep. Tom Rice said he got a call from Smith's  
office telling him that the senator would make his announcement 
Tuesday. ``But whether he was forming a third party or going with 
an existing one, I don't know,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was vacationing and not taking calls from reporters, Karen  
Hickey, his campaign spokeswoman, said Friday. ``I can't confirm, I 
can't deny,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith has said he might form his own party, or run as a  
candidate for either the Reform Party or U.S. Taxpayer Party. He 
supports low taxes, a strong national defense and school prayer. He 
strongly opposes abortion and gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform Party national chairman Russell Verney said Smith is  
welcome to seek the party's nomination if he is ready to tell 
members where he stands on economic and government reform issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Smith has strong social issues. Our party has no social  
issues,'' Verney said. ``We concentrate on economic issues and 
government reform. We tell our candidates they can state their 
social positions as individuals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, some of Smith's GOP presidential rivals also were  
quick to react. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer said, ``It would be a tragedy for the Republican  
Party to start splitting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, said, ``He's got strong convictions;  
maybe he's thinking that is what he's got to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest CNN-Gallup poll, Smith was supported by 1 percent  
of Republicans, well behind virtually every other candidate in a 
field dominated by Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	A second-term senator, Smith has said he would not resign his  
Senate seat even if he runs for the presidency as a member of a 
third party and loses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sen. Smith has long been a leader in the fight for lower  
taxes, a stronger defense and smaller government,'' said John 
Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. ``I 
trust if the reports are true that this issue will be discussed by 
the Senate Republican Conference with Sen. Smith.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would be up to the GOP conference to decide whether to  
protect Smith's seniority rights on committees. 
</P>
<P>
	His chairmanship of the Ethics Committee could be at risk, and  
he is in line to become chairman of the Environment Committee in 
the next Congress if Republicans hold their majority. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Strawberry Eager To Resume Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry says he has his life back  
on track and is determined to keep it that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't really look back. I have to really try to look forward  
at this point,'' the suspended New York Yankees outfielder said 
Friday, though he declined to speculate when he might resume his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real focus is myself and my recovery right now. Baseball  
is No. 2. Baseball is just a part of my life. I enjoy playing 
baseball, but living life and staying clean and sober is the most 
important thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry spoke as he worked out at a team facility for the  
first time since his arrest on drug and solicitation charges three 
months ago. He said alcohol and pressure he put on himself to make 
a speedy return from colon cancer surgery led to his brush with the 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight-time All-Star also said he lied about the status of  
his chemotherapy last spring because he didn't want to hurt his 
chances of making the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm done with chemotherapy now. I had mentioned I was done  
with it earlier, but I wasn't. I was covering it up to try to get 
back as soon as possible playing baseball,'' Strawberry said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My body went through some changes, some changes I've never  
experienced before in my life. It was very hard for me. I think I 
was really too hard on myself, pressing myself to do too much, 
instead of allowing myself to wait until my body started feeling 
better. I take a lot of that responsibility on myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he fell into a deep depression when the Yankees broke  
spring training and left him behind in Tampa to continue 
rehabilitation at the minor league complex. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry blamed his relapse with alcohol on himself, saying he  
``slacked off'' on attending Alcoholics Anonymous meetings. He 
spent four weeks in a rehab clinic for substance abuse in 1994 and 
was suspended for 60 days the following year after testing positive 
for cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have a tendency to come down on athletes, but we have  
people in very high positions that go through the same struggles I 
do with my alcoholism,'' Strawberry said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm clean and sober today, and that's the most important  
thing. I want to stay that way. I'm back on the right track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was arrested April 14 in Tampa and charged with  
possession of 0.3 grams of cocaine and offering an undercover 
female police officer $50 for sex. 
</P>
<P>
	He pleaded no contest six weeks later and was placed on 18  
months' probation. He also was ordered to stay out of bars and be 
tested for drugs twice a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry ran, took fly balls in the outfield and 15 minutes of  
batting practice Friday. He finished the closed workout in the 
weight room. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old outfielder was placed on administrative leave  
following his arrest. Commissioner Bud Selig said he could rejoin 
the Yankees on Aug. 11, and possibly this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was asked about those who think he doesn't deserve  
another chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things that have happened to me are things that I bring on  
myself. It's not anyone else,'' Strawberry said. ``I'm not going to 
criticize what others have to say. I just hope they wish me well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Activists March, Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITECLAY, Neb. (AP) -- American Indian activists on Saturday  
marched into town and asked four bars and a grocery to vacate this 
tiny border town, the third protest over alcohol sales and other 
issues in three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	About 80 people marched from the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation  
in South Dakota to Whiteclay. Others followed in cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The marchers drummed and sang during the two-mile walk from Pine  
Ridge, then posted signs ordering the five businesses to leave 
within 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters object to alcohol sales at the four beer stores  
that total millions of dollars each year. The grocery does not sell 
alcohol, but Indian leaders have accused its owner of racism. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcohol is banned on the reservation. One of Whiteclay's four  
beer-selling establishments lies within approximately 80 feet of 
the border. 
</P>
<P>
	After posting the notices during a walk through Whiteclay, the  
marchers, beating drums and shouting encouragement, stopped in the 
middle of the town in front of the grocery, which was looted and 
burned during a similar rally last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people plastered a large red banner across the front of the  
store that read ``American Indian Movement Grand Council.'' The 
grocery remains closed after the melee June 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Poor Bear, organizer of the three marches, said he hopes the  
tribal government will try to follow through with the eviction 
notices, even though the tribe has no legal jurisdiction in 
Whiteclay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
