<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Neo-Nazi Parade Blocked in Idaho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) -- Human rights demonstrators blocked  
an Aryan Nations parade route through downtown city streets today, 
forcing the white supremacists to make a one-block detour. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after a federal judge ruled the city couldn't move the  
marchers out of the downtown area, two dozen Aryan Nations marchers 
were outnumbered by thousands of opponents chanting ``No Nazis! No 
KKK! No fascists! USA!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three blocks into the parade, about 20 of the anti-Aryan Nations  
demonstrators sat down on Sherman Avenue and halted the march. 
Police immediately routed the Aryans down a side street. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where's that white power, guys?'' shouted protester Brad  
Nelson of Coeur d'Alene. 
</P>
<P>
	The parade lasted about 20 minutes, including the detour.  
</P>
<P>
	City officials had urged residents and visitors to shun the  
march. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, U.S. District Judge Edward Lodge derailed efforts  
by the city to move the Aryans from downtown to a route across a 
former dump site on the city's outskirts, ruling it an 
unconstitutional free-speech restriction. 
</P>
<P>
	A parade held last summer during the Aryans' annual conference  
attracted about 90 group members and supporters, and about two 
dozen of an estimated 1,400 protesters were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The summer tourist season swells Coeur d'Alene from a town of  
25,000 to about 100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a black eye on our community,'' said Malcolm  
Johnstone, a downtown businessman. ``We have to send them a message 
that this is not anything that supports community values 
whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, about 80 white supremacists and 200 opponents  
shouted and scuffled with each other at a city park before an Aryan 
Nations rally. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
