<HEADLINE> Gehrig Uniform Sells for $451,541 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The uniform Lou Gehrig was said to have worn  
when he made his famous farewell speech in 1939 was sold for 
$451,541 at auction on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount was believed to be the most ever paid for a baseball  
uniform, according to Leland's spokesman Marty Appel. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the most ever paid for any type of Yankees' equipment,  
said Appel, a former public relations director for the club. 
</P>
<P>
	Appel said the flannel pinstripe uniform worn by the Hall of  
Fame first baseman was purchased by a south Florida man who did not 
want his name made public. The winning bid was made over the phone. 
</P>
<P>
	Gehrig, dying from a rare neurological disorder, amyotrophic  
lateral sclerosis, said goodbye to New York fans in a moving speech 
at Yankee Stadium on July 4, 1939. 
</P>
<P>
	Gehrig told the packed stadium, ``I consider myself the luckiest  
man on the face of the earth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was not known if the uniform was the same one that fetched  
$306,130 from five businessmen at auction in July 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of the Gehrig uniform highlighted the final day of the  
two-day Leland auction. On the first day, Carlton Fisk's home run 
ball that won Game 6 of the 1975 World Series for the Boston Red 
Sox sold for $113,273. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
