<HEADLINE> Cockpit Smoke Diverts Jet to Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A United Airlines Boeing 777 was diverted to  
Denver on Friday evening after a report of smoke in the cockpit, 
and six crew members were hospitalized and treated for dizziness, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight 907 was heading from Newark, N.J., to San Francisco when  
the cockpit smoke prompted an alert, said Denver International 
Airport spokesman Chuck Cannon. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane landed safely shortly after 7 p.m. and the passengers  
were taken off. Crew members remained aboard and ``apparently were 
overcome by some sort of fumes or smoke,'' Cannon said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 10 flight attendants were examined by paramedics and six  
were taken to a hospital, where he said some were given oxygen for 
nausea and others complained of symptoms including scratchy throats 
and irritated eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for The Medical Center of Aurora, George Peck, said  
the six were treated for dizziness and released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
