<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 07:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Medicare Drug Benefit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid speculation that political pressures  
leading to the 2000 elections could spark a compromise, President 
Clinton will meet next week with congressional leaders of both 
parties to discuss ways to help older Americans pay for 
prescription drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a good sign that we have the Republican  
leadership with the door open,'' Clinton said about chances for a 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said he believes the House will  
approve some help with drug costs for the neediest retirees this 
year. And Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has asked the 
Finance Committee to send to the Senate Medicare overhaul 
legislation that would improve retirees' access to prescription 
coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used his weekly radio address today to promote a  
prescription drug benefit through the Medicare program and to 
encourage older Americans to seek preventive care. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since Medicare's founding in 1965, a medical revolution has  
transformed health care in America. Once the cure for many 
illnesses was a scalpel; now just as likely it's a 
pharmaceutical,'' the president said. ``That's why I made helping 
seniors afford the prescription drugs essential to modern medical 
care a key part of the Medicare plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said his plan also would eliminate the deductible in all  
co-payments for all preventive services for cancer, diabetes, 
osteoporosis and other diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes no sense for Medicare to put up roadblocks to  
screenings and then turn around and pick up the hospital bills its 
screenings might have avoided,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A White House meeting -- at which Clinton, Lott, Hastert and  
Democratic leaders Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and Sen. Tom Daschle, 
D-S.D., are expected also to discuss other topics -- has been 
scheduled for Monday, after lawmakers return from a week-long 
Independence Day recess. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure to get something done on Medicare drugs payments  
``could crush a diamond,'' said Carl Feldbaum, president of the 
Biotechnology Industry Organization, which lobbies for drug makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether all or just some retirees will get help paying their  
drug bills, and how much, will depend on how disagreements between 
Democrats and Republicans are resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Clinton's proposal, drug benefits would be available as an  
option for all 39 million Medicare beneficiaries starting in 2002. 
Initially it would provide 50 percent government coverage of 
prescription costs up to a $1,000 annual cap in exchange for a $24 
monthly premium paid by enrollees. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans say direct Medicare drug subsidies are needed only  
for the poorest beneficiaries, while others could be helped through 
the private sector. Tax breaks for those who buy private Medigap 
insurance that covers drugs are among alternatives GOP leaders are 
considering. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest projections for government surpluses, totaling close  
to $1 trillion over the next decade, have made it easier for even 
conservative lawmakers to contemplate creating an expensive new 
government benefit for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	The bigger-than-expected surplus ``makes fixing the prescription  
drug part of Medicare a reality,'' Senate Budget Committee Chairman 
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare's potential power as a political weapon threatens to  
spoil chances for a deal, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both parties feel they want to do something, and both want to  
take credit, but neither party trusts one another,'' said 
Democratic consultant Victor Kamber. ``This could just be a 
political football where both talk about it and blame the other one 
come election time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But pressure to compromise will be strong on both Democrats and  
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers know from mail and town meetings that expensive  
prescriptions rank high on the list of retirees' wish lists, said 
John Rother, public policy director for the American Association of 
Retired Persons, the nation's largest organization of older adults. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once the expectation is raised that they're going to do  
something about it, I think it's going to be very hard for them not 
to follow through,'' Rother said. ``This is going to be a voting 
issue in the next election if they don't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But while adding drug coverage to Medicare is ``popular on the  
surface,'' GOP pollster Ed Goeas said, ``polling shows people are 
concerned ... that it may cause a runaway cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican lawmakers will have some strong backup in their  
argument that Clinton's plan would overdo it. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospitals and other health care providers are mobilizing to  
protest the president's plan to get much of the $118 billion needed 
to pay for his drug benefit from curbs on Medicare payments for 
other kinds of care. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America,  
meanwhile, has already run newspaper ads cautioning that government 
involvement in the drug market could result in price controls that 
would mean less choice for retirees and dry up investment dollars 
for biomedical research. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
