<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Focusing on New Hampshire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHUA, N.H. (AP) -- Braving dark clouds, a crowd of more than  
100 quizzed Republican presidential hopeful John McCain on issues 
ranging from gun control to services for veterans, the Panama Canal 
and the line-item veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens approached McCain afterward Friday to shake his hand,  
snap photos or wish him luck. Several who had met McCain at earlier 
appearances re-introduced themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona senator has made 11 trips to New Hampshire, site of  
the nation's first primary. He has made only one to Iowa, site of 
the first caucuses, and that was largely in his capacity as 
chairman of the Senate Transportation Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain says he is not ignoring Iowa, but state party officials  
say there is no evidence that he has a campaign organization in the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	One factor in his decision to put more focus on New Hampshire  
than Iowa could be his long-standing opposition to subsidies for 
ethanol, a grain alcohol derived from corn and added to gasoline 
subsidies. Cutting off those subsidies would hurt farmers in Iowa, 
a corn-producing state. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not ruling out Iowa, but there's no doubt New Hampshire  
is very important,'' McCain said. ``I think most Iowans -- except 
for Archer Daniel Midland -- agree that these are the kinds of 
subsidies that are not good for America.'' ADM, the large 
agribusiness company, is the nation's biggest ethanol producer. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Hampshire, McCain's political strategists talk about the  
independence of New Hampshire voters while playing up McCain's 
maverick reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're putting John McCain in a state that is known for its  
contrariness and for its independence and for its unique ability to 
rally around candidates with a strong message,'' said John Weaver, 
McCain's national political director. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain needs to finish in the top three in the New Hampshire  
primary, said Mike Dennehy, the New England campaign director. 
</P>
<P>
	With that in mind, the campaign is working to increase McCain's  
name recognition, which Dennehy said stands at about 60 percent in 
New Hampshire. The campaign wants to see that figure increase to 80 
percent to 90 percent by the end of September. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has 10 New Hampshire staff members and a headquarters. In  
Iowa, by comparison, ``I haven't seen any signs of an organization 
or coalition anywhere in Iowa,'' said Will Lynch, a Republican 
consultant in Iowa who worked for Jack Kemp in 1987 when the former 
New York congressman was running. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the ethanol issue, McCain would appeal to Iowa  
voters, Lynch said. He said that while the average Iowa voter may 
not know about McCain's stance on ethanol subsidies now, they would 
once he starts campaigning in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``I honestly don't know why else he's not coming in here. He's  
got a fantastic resume and I know people respect his history and 
heroism,'' Lynch said, referring to McCain's 5 1/2 years as a prisoner 
of war in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to ethanol subsidies may be one of the elements that  
brought down the campaign of Sen. Phil Graham of Texas in the last 
presidential primary season, Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's decision largely to ignore Iowa is unusual, according  
to Kayne Robinson, chairman of Iowa's Republican Party. The other 
Republican hopefuls have set up elaborate operations, have lined up 
the support of activists and visit the state often, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all have visible, palpable presences in the state that  
you can feel and you can see,'' Robinson said. ``I don't think 
that's true of McCain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While other Republicans practically have daily contact with the  
Iowa party, it doesn't know of a McCain representative in the 
state, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We neither hear from McCain nor do we know of anyone on the  
ground there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Robinson isn't so sure that the ethanol issue was the  
deciding factor to play down Iowa. McCain's push for campaign 
finance reform probably would hurt him more than ethanol, he said. 
And the reason may be as simple as limited resources, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he just made a decision to concentrate on other places  
and that's their right,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathy Sullivan, chairwoman of the New Hampshire Democratic  
Party, said that given the crowded Republican field, McCain may be 
making the best use of his limited funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``He may be smart to take a whole pass on this thing and focus  
on breaking out in New Hampshire,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lynch called the strategy ``stupid'' because a strong Iowa  
performance can help a candidate in the New Hampshire primary. 
Candidates who don't get that surge in Iowa have to scramble to 
keep up in New Hampshire, he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
