<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newsaper Faces Contempt Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) -- A juvenile court judge is seeking  
contempt of court charges against a reporter who wrote about 
confidential court proceedings in a child custody case. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers filed Friday, Judge Kathleen Akao ordered  
reporter Robin Musitelli and attorneys for the Santa Cruz Sentinel 
to appear in court July 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Akao said they must show why they shouldn't be punished for  
violating court orders and state law prohibiting juvenile court 
documents from being reviewed by anyone other than authorized 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Musitelli reported on the case of a father who accused Child  
Protective Services of making false allegations to seize his 
methadone-addicted baby. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said the Sentinel published details of the case  
knowing public disclosure was prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentinel Editor Tom Honig said he disagreed with the judge's  
position. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand any action against a newspaper for doing  
its job, for aggressively pursuing a story,'' Honig said. ``To have 
a judge hold a newspaper in contempt seems, on the face of it, in 
violation of the First Amendment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 08:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Place in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is ignoring the calendar.  
With time running out on his presidency, he is reaching for new 
ideas rather than slowing down. He is racing around the country and 
the world rather than relaxing at Camp David or on the golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	His place in history is at stake.  
</P>
<P>
	Marked as only the second president ever to be impeached,  
Clinton is searching for a legacy based on achievements instead of 
scandal. The roaring economy is aiding his search, giving him the 
financial cushion of $5.9 trillion in expected budget surpluses 
over the next 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a lame duck on the books, but he isn't acting like one,''  
said James Thurber, director of American University's Center for 
Congressional and Presidential Studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is looking to put Social Security and Medicare on sound  
financial footings, subsidize prescription drug costs for seniors, 
tighten gun controls, build new schools, hire 100,000 new teachers, 
spend billions on child care and health care, bring peace to the 
Middle East, stabilize war-battered Kosovo and resolve the age-old 
conflict between Catholics and Protestants in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that Bill Clinton is still  
legacy-minded,'' said Norm Ornstein, a political analyst at the 
American Enterprise Institute. ``He's not going to have any desire 
to coast for the remaining 18 months of his presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to have proposals out there on these issues because  
it's not only a potential opportunity to get something done, but 
obviously these are meat and potatoes, bread and butter issues for 
Democrats,'' Ornstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurber said Clinton's presidency is far from over.  
</P>
<P>
	``He has so much energy, and he wants his legacy to be so  
positive, that he's still driving. He gets inspired when he gets 
down, it seems,'' Thurber said, referring to the impeachment ordeal 
that dominated the first months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	With his headline-grabbing proposals on Medicare and Social  
Security, Clinton demonstrated anew his knack for dominating the 
news and shaping the agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	While Republicans hold slim majorities in the House and Senate,  
Thurber said, ``I hope they remember that the president has the 
power of the veto, and presidents win 97 percent of the time on the 
veto.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What is good for Clinton, though, might not be deemed in the  
best interest of Democrats as they try to regain control of the 
House and Senate. While the president says he wants to move 
programs through Congress, Democrats may decide they would rather 
have an issue to fight in the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has told Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton they are  
free to disagree with him if it suits their political purposes, as 
the vice president seeks the presidency and the first lady pursues 
a Senate seat. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials recoil from talk about legacy-building.  
Some think it sounds like Clinton is more interested in 
resume-padding and scandal repair than in doing the peoples' 
business. The chief of staff, John Podesta, said he banned the word 
``legacy'' from White House discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the disavowals, however, Clinton has been known to fret  
about his legacy. He told CBS' Dan Rather that he was not at all 
sure that the word ``impeachment'' would show up in the first 
paragraph of his obituary. The president portrayed his impeachment 
struggle as a battle of honor rather than disgrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Former political strategist Dick Morris, in his book ``Behind  
the Oval Office,'' recounted a lengthy discussion with Clinton in 
1996 about great presidents and where he might fit in. 
</P>
<P>
	Conceding he could not be a first-tier president without a war  
or other unanticipated historical force, Clinton questioned what it 
would take to be ranked in the second tier. They discussed making 
welfare reform work, balancing the budget and breaking the back of 
international terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good list,'' Clinton said, according to Morris. ``I've got it  
down. I'll think about it a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton never talks publicly in terms of legacy, even as he pats  
his administration on the back for the strong economy and falling 
crime rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any president who talks about legacy is not in the business of  
producing one,'' said Brookings Institution political scholar 
Thomas Mann. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he is doing is perfectly consistent with his performance  
throughout his presidency,'' Mann said. ``This is an ambitious, 
energetic politician whose perhaps greatest strength is trying to 
shape the agenda, who has a knack for identifying issues and 
articulating positions that resonate with the citizens of this 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would be a mistake to somehow attribute it to  
last-minute legacy. If it is, it's foolish,'' Mann said. ``The only 
way Clinton can work the presidency is full throttle, from 
beginning to end.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 01:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Search Expands for Murder Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIDNEY, Ohio (AP) -- The search for a man suspected of killing  
three teen-age girls at his home before fatally shooting his Bible 
study teacher expanded to Kentucky after his cash machine card was 
used there, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dragnet for Lawrence Michael Hensley, 30, has extended more  
than 200 miles southeast of Sidney, the western Ohio city where 
three teens were found dead late Thursday inside Hensley's home. 
Police believe he is heavily armed. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky State Police said Hensley, who has relatives in  
Kentucky, used the bank card in the town of London on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims Sherry Kimbler and her cousin Tosha Barrett, both 16,  
had been shot several times Thursday at close range with a shotgun. 
Amy Mikesell, 14, was found stabbed in the basement. Police said 
Ms. Kimbler was Hensley's neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	A 22-year-old woman who escaped after being shot remained  
hospitalized in serious condition with leg and shoulder wounds. 
Authorities said she identified Hensley as the gunman. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Wildermuth, 37, a Bible study teacher at Hensley's church,  
was shot and killed at his house about 30 minutes after the first 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Chief Steven Wearly said Hensley knew the girls but did  
not say why they were at the home, which Hensley shared with his 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers found 24 Molotov cocktails lined up on a workbench in  
the basement. They appeared to contain gasoline, according to bomb 
squad members who detonated the devices. 
</P>
<P>
	No motive has been revealed for the shootings, but police Capt.  
Dean Kimpel said investigators were examining the possibility that 
Hensley could be part of a satanic cult. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearly said Hensley had previously been arrested on a public  
indecency charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Hensley, a worker at the Glacier Daido America automotive parts  
plant in nearby Bellefontaine, was considered an employee in good 
standing, said Jeff Wheeler, a quality assurance manager. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 11:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cipollini Wins 4th Straight Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THIONVILLE, France (AP) -- The first week of the Tour de France  
favors sprinters, and Mario Cipollini has made the most of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Living up to his billing as the ``King of Sprints,'' the  
engaging Italian on Saturday became the first rider since 1930 to 
win four straight Tour stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the spotlight moves to Lance Armstrong: arguably the  
overall favorite and certainly the emotional one, with his stirring 
comeback from testicular cancer. The American, who won the race 
prologue, is favored in Sunday's crucial time trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Already in fifth place overall, Armstrong could soon be wearing  
the leader's yellow leader's jersey again, as the race hits the 
Alps for a series of grueling mountain stages. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lance just elicits confidence, because he believes in himself  
so much,'' said Mark Gorski, general manager of Armstrong's U.S. 
Postal Service team. ``If he believes, then everybody believes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Marston, a fan from Boise, Idaho, who watched the race on  
Saturday, was more concise. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lance is just on fire,'' Marston said.  
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong stayed safely in the pack on Saturday, as his team  
tried to make sure he stayed in form for Sunday's time trial. His 
coach ordered teammates to surround him so he'd be protected from 
the wind, and wouldn't expend too much energy. 
</P>
<P>
	The seventh stage was marked by a long and gallant breakaway by  
Frenchmen Jacky Durand and Lylian Lebreton, who were caught by the 
pack with 2.5 miles to go, after lasting nearly 124 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The 142-mile route took the riders from Avesnes-sur-Helpe, near  
the Belgian border, past fields of corn to Thionville, next to 
Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
	For the seventh time in as many days, the race ended in a  
furious sprint to the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	After catching the breakaway riders, the teams leading the pack  
jockeyed to get their star sprinters into position. They were all 
there: Cipollini, Erik Zabel of Germany, Australian Stuart O'Grady, 
Belgian Tom Steels, and Jaan Kirsipuu, the Estonian who has held 
the yellow jersey since Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Zabel, who fell with 21.7 miles to go but recovered and joined  
the sprinters at the front, suddenly slipped out of his pedals with 
about 75 yards left to race. Amazingly, he stayed on the bike. 
</P>
<P>
	Cipollini suddenly had an easy path. He crossed the finish line  
by three lengths, and then took a long, satisfied look backwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirsipuu came in third, after O'Grady, and kept the yellow  
jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Cipollini's feat came 69 years after Frenchmen Charles Pelissier  
won the last four stages of the Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning four consecutive Tour de France stages doesn't seem  
real,'' he said. ``I have to thank my teammates once again, 
especially Gian Matteo Fagnini who pushed me towards the finish 
line.'' All week, the Italian's Saeco teammates have worked 
mightily to put him into winning position. 
</P>
<P>
	He moved to second place overall, trailed by O'Grady, Zabel,  
Armstrong and Spaniard Abraham Olano. 
</P>
<P>
	After the time trial, the riders have a rest day and then they  
head to the Alps. 
</P>
<P>
	But this week has belonged to Cipollini. On Friday, he had  
already entered the record books when he won a third consecutive 
stage, the first rider to do so since 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	He achieved that feat thanks to the jury's decision to  
disqualify Steels, who crossed the finish line first. Authorities 
ruled Steels had unfairly swerved out of his line and impeded the 
movement of a fellow rider, Jan Svorada of Slovakia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 11:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cipollini Wins 4th Straight Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THIONVILLE, France (AP) -- The first week of the Tour de France  
favors sprinters, and Mario Cipollini has made the most of it. 
</P>
