<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 16:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defeats China To Win World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- They captured America and now they've  
conquered the world. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team, idolized at home like no other women's sports  
team, won the World Cup on Saturday, beating China 5-4 on penalty 
kicks after a 0-0 tie. 
</P>
<P>
	With a festive gathering of 90,185 that included President  
Clinton cheering their every move, the Americans capped the most 
successful women's sporting event ever by winning their second 
championship in the most dramatic, exhausting way imaginable. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandi Chastain sent a punishing left-footed penalty kick high  
into the net to win it as the Rose Bowl crowd erupted in cheers 
that resounded off the San Gabriel Mountains. She then ripped off 
her jersey in celebration and was mobbed by her jubilant teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a team of courage,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said.  
``They just fought and fought and fought. There are two champions 
here today, and only one is taking a trophy home. 
</P>
<P>
	``America should be very proud of these young ladies.''  
</P>
<P>
	To deafening chants of U-S-A, U-S-A, the players leapt about  
with whatever energy they had left. After they received their 
championship medals, they jogged around the field carrying three 
huge American flags as the fans roared. 
</P>
<P>
	A cloudburst of confetti littered the field as goalkeeper Briana  
Scurry, who made the winning save during the penalty kicks, ran to 
the stands to slap hands with some fans. She then got down on both 
knees and saluted the crowd, which was chanting ``Scurry, Scurry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams stood hand-in-hand for photos after sharing one of  
the most intense experiences in sports -- a shootout to decide the 
most prestigious prize in soccer, a World Cup crown. 
Coincidentally, the men's World Cup final in 1994 at the Rose Bowl 
ended in a shootout after a 0-0 tie, with Brazil beating Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	China shot first and Xie Huilin hit the left corner of the net.  
Co-captain Carla Overbeck matched the goal to a huge cheer from the 
crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Haiyan Qui barely got the ball past the outstretched hands of a  
diving Scurry, and Joy Fawcett made no mistake with her shot for 
2-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Ying Liu's shot was in the middle of the net and Scurry dived  
left to get her hands on it and send it wide. Kristine Lilly almost 
nonchalantly put hers in. 
</P>
<P>
	Ouying Zhang beat Scurry, but Mia Hamm scored. That brought Sun  
Wen, the tournament's leading scorer, to the spot with the crowd in 
a frenzy. Sun put her shot to the left of Scurry for 4-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came Chastain, who was cut from the national squad in 1994  
and missed the last World Cup. But she fought her way back onto the 
team and was the biggest of several stars on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Another savior was Lilly. In the 100th minute, in 90-degree  
heat, a header by Fan Yunjie was headed off the goal line by Lilly 
with Scurry beaten. The crowd sighed, then roared at Lilly's 
championship-saving play. 
</P>
<P>
	Another star was Michelle Akers, at 33 the oldest of the  
Americans. She left the game with an injury in the final moments of 
regulation. When she played, she dominated the midfield, never 
allowing Sun to threaten. 
</P>
<P>
	China's brilliant midfielder, Yan Jin, finally got going when  
Akers left. She created several chances in the extra periods, when 
China had a big edge. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly the two best teams in the tournament -- China outscored  
opponents 19-2 heading into the final and the United States had an 
18-3 margin -- these teams have created a scintillating rivalry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans beat the Chinese 2-1 for the 1996 Olympics gold  
medal and 2-0 for the '98 Goodwill Games crown. China had won two 
of three this year, including the championship of the prestigious 
Algarve Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	But the big one went to the Americans, and the series now stands  
12-5-5 for the United States, which also won the first World Cup in 
China in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans arrived early and ready. By halftime of the third-place  
game, won by Brazil on penalty kicks, the stands were nearly 
filled. Just about everywhere youngsters with red-white-and-blue 
painted faces waved American flags. Chants of ``U-S-A, U-S-A'' 
began even as Norway and Brazil were playing. 
</P>
<P>
	When the American team marched onto the field, Akers jumped up  
and down like a schoolgirl as her teammates waved their arms above 
their heads and encouraged more cheering from a crowd already 
screaming its lungs out. 
</P>
<P>
	The wave of sound, punctuated by a U.S. Navy F-18 fly-over at  
the conclusion of the national anthem, was deafening. 
</P>
<P>
	But there wasn't much to cheer about for most of the sloppy  
game. The Chinese seemed tentative and their passes rarely 
connected until overtime . The Americans' oft-questioned defense 
was rock solid. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither goalie was tested much, and the crowds biggest reaction  
of regulation time was when the crowd booed as Clinton was shown on 
the scoreboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the whole country was caught up in this, not only fans  
of soccer but young girls,'' Clinton said. ``In some ways, it's the 
biggest sporting even of the last decade. It's new and exciting for 
the United States. It will have a very far-reaching impact, not 
only for the United States, but for the world.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 04:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis Honored at Venice Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- It's not just the French who adore Jerry Lewis.  
</P>
<P>
	The Venice Film Festival will honor Lewis with a career award  
and a showing of ``The Bellboy,'' the comic's 1960 film. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis will receive the Golden Lion career award on Sept. 11, the  
last day of the Venice festival, when his film about a hapless 
worker at a Miami hotel will be screened, organizers said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Festival director Alberto Barbera praised Lewis, 73, as an  
``inescapable point of reference for many comic authors and 
actors.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 18:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Closer Excited To Join Diamondbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Matt Mantei very much wants to keep his nickname  
``Ice Man.'' If it means the Arizona Diamondbacks finally will be 
able to cool off the opposition in the late innings, they're more 
than happy to oblige. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's game with Oakland had just begun when the  
Diamondbacks' new closer arrived at Bank One Ballpark after his 
flight from Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't wait to get here,'' he said. ``I felt like a little  
kid coming into the stadium. It was like playing in a Little League 
World Series or something. I'm just excited to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hard-throwing right-hander was a little bleary-eyed after a  
late-night farewell party with some of his Marlins' teammates after 
he learned of the trade that sent him to Arizona on Friday night. 
Still, he wanted to go to the mound Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping to get in there today,'' he said. ``But there's  
always tomorrow or the next day. I know I'm going to have some 
opportunities to pitch here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks sent reliever Vladimir Nunez, top minor-league  
prospect Brad Penny and minor league player to be named to the 
Marlins to get Mantei. General manager Joe Garagiola was able to 
avoid losing a position player on the big league roster even though 
the Marlins knew how much the Diamondbacks need a closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona has blown 14 of 29 save opportunities this season. The  
Diamondbacks knew they needed a closer to stay in the NL West race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was aware of that. I knew they'd had some tough times in the  
bullpen,'' said Mantei, who had 10 saves in 12 opportunities with 
Florida. ``It shouldn't take that much to turn it around. It should 
be fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mantei, who just turned 26, underwent arthroscopic surgery in  
1996 to repair a partially torn rotator cuff. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I was going to be able to pitch again. I just didn't  
know I'd be as strong,'' he said, ``but I'm stronger than I was 
before I had the surgery. I thank God every morning when I wake up 
and I feel great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mantei said his top pitching speed this year has been ``a couple  
at 100 mph.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The clubhouse was empty when Mantei arrived because the game had  
started. He figured out which uniform to put on, then shook hands 
with his new teammates in the dugout before trotting out to the 
bullpen between the first and second innings. 
</P>
<P>
	From there, Mantei got a first-hand look at Randy Johnson.  
Johnson has been known to throw 100 mph pitches after nine innings. 
Johnson was beaten 2-0, the latest in a series of hard-luck 
outings, but Mantei was impressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh man, that guy's amazing,'' Mantei said. ``He's a pitcher.  
He doesn't just go out there and throw 100 mph every time. He 
pitches. The guy is awesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mantei said he felt he owed the Marlins something after they  
stood by him through his rotator cuff and back injuries. But he 
said he appreciates their trading him to a team that's contending 
in just its second season, a franchise that's quickly earned a 
reputation as being generous to its players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've hard some great things about this organization,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mantei hasn't pitched since Tuesday. His only chance before the  
All-Star break will be Sunday, when the Diamondbacks conclude their 
three-game inter-league series with Oakland. Meanwhile, he had one 
top priority Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to go back to the hotel and get some sleep,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former CART Champ Vasser Struggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELKHART LAKE, Wis. (AP) -- While new teammate Juan Montoya is  
enjoying unexpected success, former CART FedEx Series champion 
Jimmy Vasser is struggling. 
</P>
<P>
	Vasser, who won the title in 1996 and then lost championship  
battles with then-teammate Alex Zanardi each of the past two 
seasons -- took some solace Saturday in qualifying sixth for the 
Texaco/Havoline 200 at Road America. 
</P>
<P>
	That matched his qualifying effort earlier this season in  
Brazil. Vasser's only better starting position was second last 
month in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty happy because that's the best qualifying run we've  
had in a while,'' Vasser said. ``It's nice to be back at the sharp 
end of the grid again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya, a 23-year-old rookie from Colombia, continued his  
strong performance, qualifying second behind pole-winner Michael 
Andretti. It is Montoya's eighth top-five start in 10 races and his 
fifth front row start. 
</P>
<P>
	The youngster, who leads the series points, has four poles and  
four wins and could match the rookie record of five victories -- by 
Nigel Mansell in 1993 -- with a win on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jimmy is a great driver and he's just had some bad luck,''  
Montoya said. ``We've had a lot of good things happen. But he'll 
win some races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is certainly no animosity between the new teammates.  
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Montoya was presented with a stylish clock for  
leading the second quarter voting in the Driver of the Year Award. 
Vasser made it a point to be there to shake Montoya's hand and 
congratulate him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy you won it, but it's my turn next,'' Vasser said  
with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HARD HIT:@ Richie Hearn slid off track and crashed hard Saturday  
during qualifying for Sunday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pushing the car trying to get another lap in for us  
before the checkered flag and I just lost it,'' said Hearn, who was 
not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Team owner John Della Penna shook his head and said, ``We're  
just having a terrible weekend. We have virtually no testing with 
this car, so we've been behind the eight ball all weekend. Richie 
was just trying to get as much out of the car for as long as he 
could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team recently switched from a Swift chassis to a Reynard.  
Hearn will start 24th in the 26-car field. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	CHEESY GUY:@ Paul Tracy won the Miller Lite 200 last month at  
Milwaukee, so a victory here Sunday would give him a Wisconsin 
sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1993 Road America winner, who will start ninth, said, ``I'd  
love to sweep the Wisconsin Champ Car races. My wife, Liisa, is 
from Crivitz, so I'm already an honorary cheesehead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe winning at Milwaukee and Road America in the same year  
would make it official.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CLOSING IN:@ Andretti's pole on Saturday was the 32nd of his  
career, moving him just a bit closer to CART record-holder Rick 
Mears. Mears, who retired in 1993, won 39 poles. 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti already holds the CART record for laps led, but needs  
to be out front for only nine laps Sunday to reach 6,000. Mears is 
a distant second in that category with 3,286. 
  	   	
</P>
