<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fu Battles Back From Layoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- Fu Mingxia has been  
fairly fantastic, despite a three-year layoff. In fact, the time 
away may have done her good. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time Olympic gold medalist continued to shine in her  
return from retirement, hitting crisp dives on the toughest 
routines attempted Saturday to win the 3-meter springboard title at 
the University Games, adding to an earlier platform win. 
</P>
<P>
	And the 5-foot-2 Fu defeated two of the world's best, making an  
Olympic bid at Sydney in 2000 all the more likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``I retired because I was tired spiritually,'' the Chinese diver  
said through an interpreter. ``Mentally, I needed a little break. 
After I had some rest during these three years, I feel very well 
psychologically. I feel very motivated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's bad news for stars like Russians Irina Lashko and Yulia  
Pakhalina, who each won titles at the 1998 World Championships in 
Fu's absence, but were relegated to silver and bronze, 
respectively, Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fu totaled 550.230 points. Lashko, runner-up to Fu on the  
springboard in Atlanta, finished with 528.300, and Pakhalina had 
521.010. 
</P>
<P>
	``These two wins are progress in my career,'' Fu said. ``I think  
this is good preparation for the 2000 Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She could become the only woman to win five Olympic diving gold  
medals in a career. 
</P>
<P>
	Platform and springboard golds in the Atlanta Games made her the  
first woman in 36 years to win both Olympic events. She also won 
the platform at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fu, who was 12 when she won her first world title, quit the  
sport shortly after Atlanta, although she had to petition the 
government for permission. Now 21, she studies economics at 
Beijing's prestigious Qinghua University. 
</P>
<P>
	She denied she was pressured to return to international  
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mallorca, the United States earned the right to defend its  
women's basketball gold medal by beating Russia 87-79 in the 
semifinals. The U.S. will meet Spain, a 67-63 winner over Ukraine, 
in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	In men's basketball, the U.S. beat Canada 87-82 in the  
quarterfinals. The United States, winner of five straight gold 
medals, will play Mexico next, while Spain and Yugoslavia also 
advance to the final four. 
</P>
<P>
	China rallied from two sets down to beat Russia for the women's  
volleyball gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba more than doubled its gold medal total at the games, which  
close Tuesday, by taking two in judo, one in fencing, and two in 
athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	World champion Yoelvis Quesada easily won the triple jump with a  
top effort of 17.40 meters, and Daymi Pernia shattered the 
University Games record in the women's 400-meter hurdles for the 
second straight day. Pernia won the gold in 53.95 seconds, with 
NCAA champion Joanna Hayes second in 54.57. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to admit today I knew I was going to win from the  
start,'' said Pernia, who has made an impressive comeback from 
right knee surgery last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hers was one of three records set at Son Moix Stadium, where  
fewer than 500 spectators turned out for track and field 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Bloom of the United States won the shot put with an event  
record 21.11 meters, lopping 0.26 meters off a mark that had stood 
since 1985. Bloom, a past NCAA champion in the discus and shot put 
for Wake Forest, earned a silver in the discus here Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	European cross country champion Sergiy Lebid of Ukraine won the  
men's 5,000 meters in 13:37.52, four hundredths of a second faster 
than Italy's Franco Fava ran in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Other men's winners were Mexico's Alejandro Lopez in the  
20-kilometer walk and Hungary's Zsolt Nemeth in the hammer. Among 
the women, Tifanny Lott-Hogan of the United States won the 
heptathlon, Romania's Claudia Iovan took the 10-kilometer walk, and 
Pavla Hamackova gave the Czech Republic gold in the pole vault. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
