<HEADLINE> Garciaparra Misses Eighth Straight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Boston's Nomar Garciaparra missed his eighth  
straight start Saturday because of a groin injury but said he'll be 
ready to play in Tuesday night's All-Star game at Fenway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll probably be in there starting, probably play an inning or  
two,'' Garciaparra said before the Red Sox met the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, third in the American League in hitting at .366,  
overtook New York's Derek Jeter in the final week of voting for the 
AL's starting shortstop spot. Garciaparra has 14 homers and 57 RBIs 
and a 17-game hitting streak. 
</P>
<P>
	He aggravated his left groin on July 2 against the Chicago White  
Sox and hasn't played since. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to hurt me (to play),'' Garciaparra said. ``It  
might actually help me to see where I'm at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston manager Jimy Williams said Garciaparra won't play Sunday  
against Atlanta in the final game before the All-Star break, He 
said the club was ``leaving the door open'' for Garciaparra to play 
Tuesday before the hometown crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's just say there's an opening if things go right,''  
Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre, the manager of the AL team, wasn't  
looking forward to having Garciaparra come out of the game early in 
favor of Jeter. Red Sox fans are expected to boo, even if their 
hometown hero leaves the game to avoid aggravating the groin more. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he doesn't play in these next two games, what do we do  
here?'' Torre said Saturday morning. ``But I'm going to wait for 
someone to tell me. I'm not going to make that decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is one of Torre's coaches for Tuesday's game and  
probably will have the final say. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
