<HEADLINE> Dierker Eager To Manage Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Houston manager Larry Dierker is ready  
to return to the Astros after next week's All-Star break, one month 
after he had a seizure in the dugout and underwent brain surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to him this morning,'' interim manager Matt Galante  
said Saturday before Houston's interleague game with Kansas City. 
``He's doing good. He's still planning on being back right after 
the All-Star break. His first game will be next Thursday against 
Detroit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker suffered a seizure in the dugout during a game on June  
13, and doctors removed tangled blood vessels in his brain. 
</P>
<P>
	``They originally said he could possibly be back after the  
break,'' Galante said. ``It's on the quicker side rather than the 
later side, but he's right on schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going into Saturday night's game, the Astros were 11-14 in  
Dierker's absence, one game behind Cincinnati in the NL Central. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last four or five times I talked to him and saw him, he  
looked good and sounded great,'' Galante said. ``There's nothing he 
can't do but drive a car. He won't be able to drive for about five 
or six months. It's a state law that after a seizure like that you 
can't operate a vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``But other than that, he's doing great.''  
</P>
<P>
	Galante said not driving will be no problem.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll make whatever arrangements we need to make. We'll drive  
him back and forth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
