<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Wreaks Havoc in Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbs struggling to put their lives  
back together after NATO bombing were confronted with new troubles 
Saturday: flooding that forced some to flee their homes and left 
parts of the capital without power or drinking water. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight storms wreaked havoc with railway and road traffic  
throughout Serbia and even set off an air-raid siren in one town, 
causing panic among some residents who thought NATO bombing had 
resumed. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one death was reported and 10 people were missing, the  
private Beta news agency said. A 60-year-old man drowned Friday 
night in the swollen Lugomir River while trying to rescue his 
cattle in a village near the town of Jagodina, 60 miles southeast 
of Belgrade, Beta reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``This must be a punishment from God. First NATO nearly  
destroyed everything I had, then this. ... Could it be worse?'' 
said Petko Budimir, 40, whose rented house was flooded. His 
previous home was nearly destroyed when NATO bombed Belgrade's 
Strazevica suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	The area was a frequent target during NATO's 78-day air campaign  
against Yugoslavia, which was launched to force Belgrade to accept 
a peace plan for the Serbian province of Kosovo. The bombing ended 
in early June. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers used inflatable boats to evacuate residents from  
several buildings in another Belgrade suburb, Rakovica. Debris was 
strewn across streets in the area as local residents struggled to 
build a sandbag barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Some parts of Belgrade were without drinking water and  
electricity, the Politika TV station reported Saturday. The 
capital's main emergency hospital was flooded, and health workers 
issued a plea that only emergency patients be brought in. 
</P>
<P>
	An international train traveling from Belgrade to the Bulgarian  
capital, Sofia, was blocked overnight in a Belgrade suburb after 
flooding wrecked a stretch of track. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no reports of heavy flooding to the west in  
Yugoslavia's other republic, Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	As heavy rains continued Saturday in Serbia, Beta said the main  
highway from Belgrade to Nis in southeastern Serbia was cut near 
the town of Jagodina by a landslide. High water cut a rail line in 
the area, where a state of emergency was declared, Beta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also expressed concern about high water threatening a  
dam on the Gruza River near Kraljevo, 75 miles south of Belgrade. A 
local Kraljevo radio station warned residents near the dam to leave 
the area, Beta said, and the state-run Tanjug news agency said 
there was danger the whole area could be flooded. 
</P>
<P>
	The daily Vecernje Novosti reported Saturday that heavy rain in  
the town of Trstenik, 95 miles south of Belgrade, set off an 
air-raid warning siren, prompting some residents to flee their 
homes for fear of air attacks. They returned after local radio 
repeatedly broadcast a message that the alert was an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	In the central Serbian city of Kragujevac, floods caused a power  
blackout and disrupted the city's regular water supply. Lightning 
sparked a number of fires, Beta said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
