<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 23:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jeter Bats Cleanup for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Derek Jeter moved into the cleanup spot of the  
New York Yankees' batting order for the first time in his career, 
going 0-for-4 in Saturday's 9-8 loss to New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter's average dropped from a league-leading .377 to .373 --  
second to the .375 for Toronto's Tony Fernandez. Jeter had batted 
second in 71 games this year and hit third 11 times. He also batted 
leadoff once. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has a plan. He goes up there and gives us his money's  
worth,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``He's probably been the 
most consistent of any of our players this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter struck out in the first, grounded out in the fourth, flied  
out in the sixth, was intentionally walked in the seventh and 
grounded out in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I said earlier, you're only your number in the order in  
your first at-bat,'' he remarked, saying the switch didn't mean 
much. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was designed to get Bernie Williams back to the No. 2  
spot. Williams, the Yankees' cleanup hitter in recent years, hit 
second last month when Jeter was dropped to third. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last time we put him there, it seemed to put us on fire,''  
Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Knoblauch remained in the leadoff spot, Paul O'Neill hit  
third and Tino Martinez batted fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way I could split the left-handers up was to do  
this,'' Torre said, a reference to O'Neill and Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre pulled Jeter aside when the Yankees arrived at Shea  
Stadium about 2 1/2 hours before the first pitch. Williams didn't mind 
the shift. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him he was hitting second, he said, `OK.' If I told him  
he was hitting fourth, he'd say, `OK,''' Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter lost out to Boston's Nomar Garciaparra in fan voting for  
the starting AL shortstop in Tuesday's All-Star game at Fenway 
Park. Garciaparra missed his eighth straight game Saturday after 
injuring his groin July 2 against the Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he doesn't play in these next two games, what do we do  
here?'' said Torre, the American League's manager. ``But I'm going 
to wait for someone to tell me. I'm not going to make that 
decision.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
