<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Planes Depart for Polar Aid Mission  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- Two U.S. Air Force planes took  
off Sunday on a medical aid mission to Antarctica. They're dropping 
medication and diagnostic equipment to a worker who discovered a 
lump in her breast but can't immediately leave the frigid 
continent. The 47-year-old woman might not be evacuated from 
Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station until late October, the earliest 
time aircraft can land safely. A weather report from the pole 
Sunday morning said the weather was good, with the surface 
temperature at 85 degrees below zero, several degrees warmer than 
the past few days. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Women Capture World Cup  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The U.S. team defeated China 5-4  
Saturday on penalty kicks to capture the Women's World Cup soccer 
title. When Brandi Chastain's left-footed kick landed high in the 
net, the Rose Bowl erupted in cheers. U.S. goalie Briana Scurry had 
stopped Liu Ying's shot with the penalty score at 2-2. The game 
remained 0-0 after regulation and two 15-minute overtime. President 
Clinton was one of the 90,185 spectators at the biggest women's 
sporting event in American history. ``It was the most exciting 
sports event I have ever seen,'' Clinton told the victorious U.S. 
athletes. 

</P>
<P>
	Britain Investigates Kosovo Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Britain's Defense Ministry said Sunday it is  
investigating the British paratroopers in Kosovo who opened fire 
this month on a Kosovo Liberation Army car, killing two rebels. A 
Defense spokesman said the soldiers have not been charged with any 
crime and are still on active duty. Official reports on the 
incident said the soldiers opened fire on the vehicle because they 
feared their lives were at risk from a man firing celebratory shots 
into the air from the roof of the car. But witnesses have said the 
paratroopers did not do enough to warn the people in the car and 
that no attempt was made to stop the vehicle. 

</P>
<P>
	Bill Bradley Focuses on Race  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley  
told thousands of NAACP delegates Saturday night that matters of 
racial justice would get top priority in his administration. 
``Quite frankly, race is the reason I'm in politics,'' Bradley said 
in brief comments to a gathering of 3,500 at a gospel show to start 
the NAACP's 90th annual convention. Bradley, a former New Jersey 
senator, explained that watching the discussion and successful vote 
on the 1964 civil rights bill helped push him towards a life of 
political service. 

</P>
<P>
	House GOP Seeks 10 Pct. Tax Cut  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans on Saturday proposed an $864  
billion plan to cut income taxes by 10 percent during the next 
decade. The GOP proposal was directly at odds with White House 
efforts to focus budget surpluses on Social Security, Medicare and 
some new spending. ``If we don't cut taxes now and the money stays 
in Washington, the politicians will surely spend it,'' said House 
Ways and Means chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, the architect of the 
Republican plan. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Discuss China Bomb Payments  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is sending  
officials to Beijing to discuss payments for 20 people injured and 
families of three killed in the mistaken U.S. bombing of the 
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia. The State Department said 
Saturday that Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering ``conveyed 
our willingness to provide a humanitarian payment'' when he visited 
Beijing last month to apologize for the ``awful tragedy'' of the 
May 7 bombing. Department legal adviser David Andrews will head the 
delegation going to the Chinese capital this coming week, the 
department said. 

</P>
<P>
	Conrad To Be Buried With Honors  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Apollo 12 astronaut Pete Conrad, the  
third man to walk on the moon, will be buried with full military 
honors in Arlington National Cemetery. Conrad was killed in a 
motorcycle accident Thursday in Southern California. He was 69. The 
burial will be July 19. 

</P>
<P>
	Twins Edge Pirates 5-4  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Pinch-hitters Terry Steinbach and Ron Coomer  
hit RBI singles with one out in the bottom of the ninth inning and 
the Minnesota Twins rallied past the Pittsburgh Pirates 5-4 
Saturday night. The Twins had been 0-45 when trailing after eight 
innings. The Pirates lost their eighth straight game indoors since 
a win at Houston on May 14, 1998. Todd Walker led off the Twins 
ninth with a double against Jason Christiansen. Mike Williams 
(1-1), activated from the disabled list Friday after being out 
because of tendinitis in his right shoulder, then relieved. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
