<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Dramatic Homer For Piazza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Another day, another three-run homer against the  
New York Yankees for Mike Piazza. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be a big step for us,'' he said after the Mets'  
dramatic 9-8 victory Saturday over their crosstown rival. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 6, Piazza hit a two-run homer off Roger Clemens as the  
Mets won 7-2 at Yankee Stadium, stopping an eight-game losing 
streak and Clemens' 20-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday night, he broke a sixth-inning tie with a three-run  
homer that gave the Mets a 5-2 victory over the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, with the Mets trailing 6-4 in the seventh, he reached  
down for a low pitch from Ramiro Mendoza and hit a three-run homer, 
a 482-foot drive that bounced off a tent behind the left-field 
bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza didn't even watch it, afraid of being called a showboat.  
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to look up,'' he said. ``I just wanted to get  
around the bases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza is showing the Mets made a good investment when they  
signed him to a $91 million, seven-year contract after last season. 
He's homered in three straight games, going 2-for-3 with four RBIs 
Saturday. Piazza is hitting .311 with a team-high 19 homers and 55 
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always been a streaky hitter,'' he said. ``You go through  
times of the year when you come through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When it happens against the Yankees, everyone in New York takes  
notice -- especially when it happens in three straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	On the back pages of the tabloids and on talk radio, the Yankees  
and Mets compete for attention. Some think there's a battle between 
Piazza and the Yankees' Derek Jeter for the title of biggest star 
in town. 
</P>
<P>
	Not Piazza. His focus is on returning the Mets to the postseason  
for the first time since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel any competition,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
