<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four More Satellites Put in Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Four more Globalstar communication  
satellites rocketed into orbit today in the second launch of its 
kind in a month. 
</P>
<P>
	A Boeing Delta II rocket took off at 4:45 a.m. The satellites --  
worth about $15 million each -- separated in pairs about an hour 
later. High wind had forced a two-day launch delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Globalstar, based in San Jose, Calif., plans to begin providing  
wireless telephone service this fall. Today's launch boosted the 
number of Globalstar satellites in orbit to 28; altogether, 48 
satellites are planned. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Globalstar launch is planned for later this month and  
yet another in August, also aboard Delta rockets. Four satellites 
were placed in orbit June 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's launch cost about $115 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The Globalstar consortium of 12 companies was founded by Loral  
Space and Communications Ltd. and Qualcomm Inc. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
