<DOCNO> APW19990710.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 09:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Image Everything in Maligned Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For Tim Watkins, the image of Watts as a  
blighted neighborhood is sometimes just as stubborn a foe as the 
crime and unemployment he confronts as youth director of local 
social service agency. 
</P>
<P>
	As President Clinton's visit this past week refocuses the  
nation's attention on communities such as Watts, Watkins hopes 
Americans get a glimpse of the good as well as the bad. 
</P>
<P>
	That is crucial for Watkins and others who are trying to spur  
commerce in such areas. Businesses that can bring jobs and 
investment to a community often are frightened away by the 
inner-city image of gangs, violence and poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	A case in point came only Wednesday, when a TV news crew  
canceled an interview about Clinton's visit to cover a hostage 
situation a few miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me that's a significant indicator of what makes the news in  
Watts. It's generally negative and sensational, in that order,'' 
said Watkins, who works for the Watts Labor Community Action 
Committee. ``On the one hand it reinforces the impression that this 
is a dangerous, nasty and ugly place, and on the other hand it robs 
us of an opportunity to show people what's positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton visited South Los Angeles Thursday as part of a four-day  
national tour to promote private and public investment in 
underserved communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment in South Los Angeles has increased since the 1992  
riots, but community leaders say much more is needed if residents 
are to feel the benefits of the nation's long economic expansion. 
They hope Clinton's visit will help erase negative images and 
convince more banks and corporations that there are profitable 
markets to be tapped in inner-city neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're looking at it from afar, all you see is that  
image,'' said Shari Berenbach, executive director of the Calvert 
Foundation, a Bethesda, Md.-based nonprofit spinoff of the socially 
conscious Calvert Group mutual funds. The foundation oversees a 
separate investment fund that targets undeveloped communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Negative images that frighten investors also diminish the  
aspirations of young people growing up in poor communities, Carolyn 
Martin said as she stood across the street from Southwest College 
to catch a glimpse of Clinton as he drove by. Martin tries to raise 
expectations of youth as education coordinator for a local office 
of the Congress of Racial Equality. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to turn the whole mindset around,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	In Watts, the image is etched deep in Americans' minds. Most  
know the community as the scene of violent riots in 1965. The 
community erupted again, along with the rest of South Los Angeles, 
in 1992 after white police officers were acquitted in the 
videotaped beating of Rodney King. 
</P>
<P>
	As outside businesses make contact and get to know the people in  
underdeveloped communities, good investment opportunities will 
become apparent, Berenbach said. 
</P>
<P>
	The potential market for lenders in Watts and other similar  
areas is big. Minority-owned businesses are growing at double the 
rate of all firms in the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent estimate by the Chicago-based business coalition Social  
Compact places the number of minority firms at nearly 2 million 
with total sales of $205 billion. Demand for capital in the 
minority business community is estimated to be in excess of $144 
billion per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax incentives included in Clinton's plan might make it easier  
for both businesses and individuals to invest in communities such 
as Watts. The proposal includes a 30 percent income tax credit on 
earnings from stock or other equity interests in selected community 
development organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Such equities, Berenbach said, typically offer a return of 3  
percent or 4 percent. Under the new program, investors could add 
another 6 percent a year, spread over five years, for such 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's proposal would allow up to $6 billion in such  
equities to be issued between 2000 and 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvert's fund, Calvert Community Investments, has sold $9.6  
million worth of these equities over the past four years. Berenbach 
believes many investors who are now reluctant to put their money in 
poor communities would be attracted to the prospect of greater 
gains through a government-sponsored program. 
</P>
<P>
	As activists in Watts and similar communities try to change the  
perceptions of investors and corporate executives, they also battle 
to keep their children and neighbors from accepting the negative 
images. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1992 riots, many people in South Los Angeles have been  
infused with a new spirit of self-reliance that is spreading, said 
John Bryant, founder of Operation Hope, a private group that works 
with banks to give inner-city residents access to loans and classes 
about financial responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	After the riots, people looked back on years of neglect and  
realized they had to depend on themselves, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It forced people to be innovative in the way they looked at  
their lives, they could no longer afford to be intellectually or 
spiritually lazy,'' he added. ``And once they were forced to use 
those new tools, they kind of said, 'Hey, this works.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
