<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Copes With Narrow GOP Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After days of gridlock, Majority Leader Trent  
Lott stood at his desk to announce a classic Senate deal: Democrats 
would allow swift passage of routine spending bills, as he wanted, 
in exchange for the health care debate they sought. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to have some trust,'' the Mississippi Republican said.  
``We have to give the benefit of the doubt to the leaders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His comments seemed directed not so much at Democratic  
lawmakers, who are united enough to thwart Lott at numerous turns, 
as at his own fractious GOP rank and file. 
</P>
<P>
	And with good reason.  
</P>
<P>
	Senate rules give extraordinary power to a determined minority,  
or even to a single senator, and Lott also must contend with a 
skillful president of the opposite party. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he has been buffeted by dissent within his  
party. Government spending, foreign policy and gun control have 
brought increased unhappiness in recent months, particularly among 
conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Some GOP senators are ``grumbling, but I don't know that they're  
that unhappy,'' said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala. ``We're all 
grown-ups here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in his Capitol office shortly after a  
gun-control debate in which Republicans first rejected and then 
accepted new restrictions on gun-show sales, Lott brushed aside a 
question of whether his three-year tenure had hit a rough spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think so at all,'' he said. Since he gained his post  
in 1996, he said, Congress has passed a balanced budget plan, a tax 
cut and overhauls of Medicare and immigration laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hope to send Clinton another tax cut this year, as  
well as legislation to lock up the Social Security surplus. Lott 
also wants to narrow differences with the administration on 
spending bills and avoid year-end concessions of the type that 
infuriated many Republicans last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott also has struggled with political fallout from articles  
describing a 1992 appearance before the Council of Conservative 
Citizens, an organization that has been condemned as racist. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the controversy flared in the same time frame as  
impeachment and charged that anonymous allies of President Clinton 
were behind it. ``We have reason to believe that they had 
investigators in my state combing around,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They couldn't find women problems. They couldn't find money  
problems. So the only thing they could come up with was I spoke to 
a group that has some members who espouse views that I don't agree 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott conceded, ``A lot of this is innuendo and hearsay.''  
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said, ``I don't know  
what Senator Lott is talking about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That issue aside, numerous Republican aides, speaking on  
condition of anonymity, said GOP senators freely criticize Lott in 
private. They complain he does not attack the Democrats 
aggressively enough and does not forcefully advance a conservative 
GOP agenda. Some worry that Lott will not be strong enough in 
combating demands to lift the spending caps put in place in the 
1997 balanced budget agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	While Lott can jab Clinton -- he's holding up the president's  
nominee for the United Nations, for example -- aides say senators 
grumble he sometimes cares more about checking items off a 
legislative to-do list than with content of the bills. 
</P>
<P>
	An emergency spending bill grew so costly last spring that 23 of  
the other 54 Republicans voted against it, including two other GOP 
leaders. ``I said it sucks, but we ought to pass it,'' Lott told 
reporters after a closed-door caucus where Republicans aired their 
unhappiness. 
</P>
<P>
	With other Republicans demanding that ``pork barrel'' spending  
be cut out of the measure, Lott agreed to take out a $7 million 
provision he had included for a storm-damaged National Guard armory 
in Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the Capitol, the tensions within the GOP leadership have  
become evident in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's relationship with the No. 2 Republican senator, Don  
Nickles of Oklahoma, is not a close one. Nickles constantly presses 
Lott to deal more aggressively with the top Democrat, Sen. Tom 
Daschle of South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's ties with the third-ranking Republican, Sen. Larry Craig  
of Idaho, were strained by the gun-control debate, in which Craig 
played a prominent role. 
</P>
<P>
	The majority leader's defenders point to the Republicans' 55-45  
edge in the Senate -- a majority but not ``a practical majority, 
because on any given thing you lose four or five votes,'' said Tom 
Korologos, a lobbyist who has studied the Senate's ways for 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, he said, ``there's no stable farm club'' of  
conservative Democrats willing to side regularly with Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus, if Daschle is able to hold together 41 Democrats, he can  
use the Senate's filibuster rules to thwart GOP legislation and win 
votes on his own agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the case on gun control and on health care, which is  
due up in the Senate this week. Democrats are planning to force GOP 
senators to vote on several amendments with strong public support. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control caused a near meltdown in May, when Republicans were  
forced into a series of embarrassing apologies and retreats in 
lengthy floor debate. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, a White House-backed bill passed the GOP-controlled  
Senate, with Vice President Al Gore jubilantly casting a key 
tie-breaking vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans seethed privately that Lott had handed a  
lifeline to Gore, whose White House campaign was struggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
