<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Urged To Think Globally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Minority journalists should take a global view in  
their coverage of the news, panelists at the Unity '99 convention 
said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must, in a multicultural society, learn to think  
multiculturally, not just in the boxes that we've become accustomed 
to. The global village must begin to think globally and not just 
nationally, which we're not accustomed to,'' said the Rev. Jesse 
Jackson, one of the speakers at ``America's Brave New World: Heaven 
or Hell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The media cannot just suck up the jet fumes of nationalist  
leaders. It must in fact try to think globally as well,'' Jackson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 6,000 minority journalists, editors and reporters have  
been meeting here this week for the Unity '99 convention. 
</P>
<P>
	International law, human rights, self-determination, economic  
justice and consistency should become the moving forces of world 
development, ``as opposed to oil and water routes, land and 
ideology,'' said Jackson, the head of Operation Push and the 
Rainbow Coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The challenge for us as journalists is getting Americans to  
realize that the news isn't just what's happening in our back yard 
or on our front porch ... We need to make people understand that 
foreign news is not just news about the latest saga of the British 
royals,'' said Vicki Mabrey, CBS ``60 Minutes II'' correspondent. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States also ``lacks knowledge of Asia and ... is  
culturally insensitive,'' said Ronnie Chan, chairman of the Hong 
Kong-United States Economic Cooperation Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Strains in China-U.S. relations over revelations of nuclear  
spying have led to ``a racial profiling of Chinese-Americans as 
part of the China-bashing'' in Congress, said George Koo, managing 
director of International Strategic Alliances Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Chinese-Americans have been racially profiled, then all  
Asian-Americans are in the same boat,'' Koo said. ``You, ladies and 
gentlemen, can do something about this. Bring the Asian-American 
perspective into the discussion when the U.S.-China relation is 
being discussed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As media people, we should all remember that racial profiling  
begins at home,'' warned another panelist, Suzan Shown Harjo, 
president of Morning Star Institute, an Indian rights group. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who are in law enforcement, people who are in the FBI,  
where do they get these notions from?'' Harjo said. ``When we 
stereotype ourselves and each other in the press ... that can be 
used against us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
