<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meadowlands Pace Elims Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Grinfromeartoear, Sign of Success  
and longshot Blissfull Hall scored victories Saturday night in the 
legally marred eliminations for the $1 million Meadowlands Pace. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a state appeals court ordered the Meadowlands  
Racetrack to redraw the fields for the three eliminations because 
it said the track had erred in not dividing trainer Brett Pellings' 
six entrants evenly among the three races. 
</P>
<P>
	After the track tried to fix the error on Thursday, Robert  
Glazer, the owner of Peter Pan Stables, filed a complaint and the 
court sided with him. 
</P>
<P>
	With the fields redrawn, Glazer managed to get two of his three  
horses into next Saturday night's final, although his heavily 
favored The Panderosa was just nipped at the wire by Blissfull Hall 
in the third elimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Pelling got three horses in the final, including The Panderosa  
and Grinfromeartoear. 
</P>
<P>
	Driven by Ron Pierce, Blissfull Hall posted the fastest winning  
time of 1.51.1. 
</P>
<P>
	The top three finishers in each elimination and the fastest  
fourth-place finisher advanced to next week's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Grinfromeartoear was never challenged in winning the first  
elimination in 1:51.3. Jack Moiseyev moved Grinfromeartoear to the 
lead around the half-mile pole and they led by more than two 
lengths at the top of the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Badlands Hanover closed late with Pierce, finishing a  
half-length behind the winner and a half ahead of Washington VC, 
driven by George Brennan, 
</P>
<P>
	Grinfromeartoear paid $11.20, $3.60 and $2.60 in winning for the  
third time in seven starts this year for Pelling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brett told me he was the best,'' Moiseyev said after driving  
Grinfromeartoear for the first time. ``He was real sharp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luc Ouellette also made his first drive with Sign of Success a  
winning one in taking the second elimination by 2 1/2 lengths over the 
John Campbell-driven Stutzpan. New Jersey Classic winner Art's 
Conquest, Pelling's other finalist, overcame the No. 10 post to 
finish third. 
</P>
<P>
	Sign of Success, who didn't win in his first five starts this  
year, paid $13.80, $9.20 and $3.80 in capturing his third straight 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	Blissfull Hall rallied from fifth at top of the stretch to nip  
The Panderosa by a nose in the final elimination. Mystical Shark 
was third and Goliath Bayama got the final spot in next week's 
final by finishing fourth in 1:51.3. 
</P>
<P>
	Blissfull Hall paid $58.80, $13.20 and $6 in winning for the  
second time in three starts. 
</P>
<P>
	The $160,000 Arthur J.Cutler Memorial for trotters, the richest  
race on the card, was won easily by Kick Tail. The Berndt 
Lindstedt-driven 4-year-old covered the mile in a career-best 
1:54.1 and paid $6.40, $4.80 and $3.60. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
