<DOCNO> APW19990710.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 01:00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trucker in Amtrak Accident Ran Sign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAGLE LAKE, Texas (AP) -- The driver of a truck involved in an  
Amtrak derailment will be charged with failing to stop for an 
approaching train, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He saw the train coming, but it was too late,'' Texas  
Department of Public Safety spokesman Tom Vinger said Friday. ``We 
think in essence he ran the stop sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Bubela, 21, of El Campo, Texas, also faces possible  
citations for failure to have a log book and faulty brakes, Vinger 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Bubela's employer, Key Energy Services of New  
Brunswick, N.J., declined comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunset Limited was headed Thursday from Los Angeles to  
Orlando, Fla., when it slammed into Bubela's rig, flipping 10 of 
its 13 cars off the tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty of the 235 passengers and an engineer were injured. Most  
were treated for bumps and bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no warning lights or gates at the rural crossing  
about 62 miles west of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be looking at why the accident occurred, doing  
interviews with some people, some sight-distance testing and 
checking the speed of the train,'' said Keith Holloway, a spokesman 
for the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Holloway said the train's event recorder was recovered from the  
lead engine and has been sent to Washington for review by crash 
experts. 

</P>
