<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Wet, stormy weather was scattered from the Southwest to the  
Northeast on Saturday as a cool front pushed across the nation, and 
thunderstorms also were scattered over the Gulf states. 
</P>
<P>
	In the cooler air behind the front, temperatures fell to record  
lows of 38 at Pocatello, Idaho; 46 at Rapid City, S.D.; 46 at North 
Platte, Neb., and 49 at Goodland, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Moisture streaming along the cold front helped produce showers  
and thunderstorms from Texas across the Mississippi and Ohio 
Valleys into New England. 
</P>
<P>
	During the afternoon, as the cold front pressed slowly  
southward, storms grew more numerous from central Texas to eastern 
Kentucky and across the Tennessee Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Locally heavy rain fell in central Texas, and flash flood  
warnings were posted for several counties. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered thunderstorms and showers also developed along much of  
the Gulf Coast, from southern Texas to the Florida Panhandle, 
becoming more numerous and expanding inland during the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Southwest, afternoon showers and thundershowers developed  
across parts of Arizona and New Mexico, with a few showers 
extending from Arizona into adjacent sections of southern 
California, Nevada and Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a few showers were possible in North Dakota and  
northern Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 35 at Stanley, Idaho, to early afternoon readings of 
95 at Salisbury, Md.; Fort Belvoir, Va., and Phoenix. The lowest 
wind chill was 22 at Malta, Idaho, and the highest heat index by 
early afternoon was 121 at Salisbury, Md. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
