<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palmer Sees The End Coming  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Shortly after missing the cut at  
the U.S. Senior Open, Arnold Palmer climbed aboard his plane and 
flew back to Latrobe, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	He had plenty to think about on the way.  
</P>
<P>
	Frustrated by his play in the Open, Palmer said if his game did  
not come around, he would not be playing in many more tournaments. 
One of the best ever to grace a golf course can see the end coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is terrible, the last two days,'' Palmer said Friday. ``I  
don't know that I will play much more competition like this. I may 
play a few tournaments, a Masters or something like that. But 
unless I start hitting it a lot better in Latrobe, I am not going 
to take it anywhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he never used the word `retire' and even named some  
tournaments in which he planned to play, Palmer noted, ``Well, I 
guess everything has to come to an end somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most popular golfer in history, Palmer couldn't  
break 80 in the Open, shooting rounds of 81 and 84. Friday's 84, 
which included a two-stroke penalty for an illegal putting stance 
as he was tapping in on No. 18, was his worst score ever in the 
Senior Open. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time he didn't make the cut was 1991.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have some commitments this year which I will finish, some  
events that I have committed to, but other than that, that is about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, who turns 70 on Sept. 10, said he'll play in a seniors  
tournament in Boston in August and probably will play in next 
year's Senior Open at Saucon Valley in his home state of 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am happy to be here. I am not happy about the way I  
played,'' Palmer said. ``But I am not saying I am not going to play 
again, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer has four Masters championships and two British Open  
titles among his 92 victories worldwide. His last victory on the 
senior tour came in 1988, but he remains one of the game's most 
enduring figures -- a fact that was evident in this tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Huge crowds followed Palmer during his rounds at the Des Moines  
Golf and Country Club and applauded his every step. At times, it 
seemed as if he spent more time tipping his cap than wearing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I enjoy playing golf and I will probably never give up  
playing,'' Palmer said. ``So that tells you the answer to that. I 
have always said when I can't enjoy playing out here and having the 
competition as a part of my existence, then I will discontinue the 
competition and play at home with my foursome.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
