<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silverbulletday Wins at Oceanport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OCEANPORT, N.J. (AP) -- Super filly Silverbulletday took the lead  
at the top of the stretch and romped to a five-length victory 
against three rivals in the $250,000 Monmouth Breeders' Cup Oaks on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was Silverbulletday's first since finishing seventh in  
the Belmont Stakes against males, and this one was really no 
contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Jerry Bailey let Silverbulletday get comfortable for the  
first half mile, challenged pacesetter Bag Lady Jane on the final 
turn and then drew off in the stretch to the cheers of the crowd of 
12,402 at Monmouth Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday covered the mile and a sixteenth for 3-year-olds  
in a leisurely 1:43 in winning for the sixth time in seven starts 
this year and for the 12th time in 14 career outings. The 
3-year-old daughter of Silver Deputy paid $2.10 and earned $150,000 
for owner Michael Pegram. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no place or show wagering. Of the $157,535 in the win  
pool at the track, $123,995 was bet on Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	The filly has earned $1.25 million this year, pushing her career  
total to $2.36 million. It was her ninth graded stakes win and it 
also gave trainer Bob Baffert his first win ever in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Boom Town Girl closed in the stretch under Tommy Turner to edge  
Bag Lady Jane by a length for second. Chatter Patter was a distant 
fourth, another 12 1/4 lengths farther back. West's Secret was an 
early scratch. 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Aaron Gryder put Bag Lady Jane on the lead from the  
inside post and the Canadian-bred filly led the small field through 
the opening half mile in 47.1 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey and Silverbulletday started from the outside No. 4 and  
they went four wide into the first turn. Silverbulletday moved into 
second early in the backstretch and then waited to make her move. 
</P>
<P>
	The ease of the race was nothing like Silverbulletday's race in  
the Belmont when her eight-race winning streak was snapped. The 
filly was on the lead early with Kentucky Derby and Preakness 
winner Charismatic challenging all the way. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
