<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Body of Cuban Migrant Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- U.S. Coast Guard crews on Saturday found the body  
of a migrant Cuban woman who disappeared after a boat collided with 
a Coast Guard cutter and sank. 
</P>
<P>
	Her body was found about 45 miles north of the spot where a  
motorized 25-foot wooden boat carrying 12 Cubans collided with the 
cutter at about 11 p.m. Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven people were rescued.  
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard ships and helicopters searched for the woman in a  
600-mile area in the waters off Florida. Officials would not 
comment on her cause of death until an autopsy was performed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans' boat was attempting to cut across the bow of the  
cutter 10 miles east of Hillsboro Inlet, which is about 36 miles 
north of Miami. The collision sank the boat in six minutes, said 
Jeff Murphy, a Coast Guard spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Under U.S. policy, foreigners who reach U.S. shores are allowed  
to seek asylum, but those intercepted at sea are returned to their 
homeland or another country. 
</P>
<P>
	The rescued Cubans were moved to another Coast Guard cutter and  
transported to Freeport, Bahamas. From there, they were to be taken 
to the U.S. Naval Base at Cuba's Guantanamo Bay, where they will be 
interviewed and repatriated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, this is the direct responsibility of Fidel Castro  
whose 40 year dictatorial grip over the Cuban people causes them to 
throw themselves to the sea in search of the freedom we take for 
granted,'' Gov. Jeb Bush said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash comes amid tension between Cuban exiles in Miami and  
the Coast Guard in the wake of an incident June 29, when eight 
Coast Guardsmen used pepper spray and fire hoses on six Cubans 
trying to make it to shore. 
</P>
<P>
	Live television broadcasts of the incident enraged many of  
Miami's Cuban community, who protested the Coast Guard's actions by 
blocking traffic on two major roadways. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight Coast Guardsmen were removed this week from law  
enforcement duty pending an internal investigation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
