<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tour de France Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THIONVILLE, France (AP) -- A look at Saturday's seventh stage of  
the 86th Tour de France: 
</P>
<P>
	STAGE: A 142 mile ride that began at Avesnes-sur-Helpe, near the  
Belgian border, to Thionville, next to Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
	STAGE WINNER: Italy's Mario Cipollini, riding for the Saeco  
team, won his fourth straight stage, edging out his rivals in a 
time of 5 hours, 26 minutes 59 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	HOW OTHERS FARED: Australia's Stuart O'Grady finished second and  
Jaan Kirsipuu of Estonia was third. Saturday's stage was marked by 
a long breakaway by Frenchmen Jacky Durand and Lylian Lebreton, who 
were caught by the pack with 2.5 miles to go. 
</P>
<P>
	OVERALL STANDINGS: Estonia's Jaan Kirsipuu did well enough to  
retain the yellow jersey. Cipollini remained in second place, 14 
seconds behind the leader. O'Grady moved into third place, 34 
seconds back. American Lance Armstrong edged up to fifth place, 54 
seconds behind. 
</P>
<P>
	TOUR TIDBITS: Cipollini made cycling history by becoming the  
first rider since 1930 to win four consecutive Tour de France 
stages. He broke the record held by Frenchmen Charles Pelissier, 
who won the last four stages of the Tour 69 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	QUOTE OF THE DAY: ``Winning four consecutive Tour de France  
stages doesn't seem real,'' Cipollini said. 
</P>
<P>
	NEXT STAGE: Sunday, a crucial 35-mile time trial in the city of  
Metz. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
