<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Protest Low Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SWEETGRASS, Mont. (AP) -- Farmers and ranchers in Montana and  
North Dakota held rallies aimed at getting the federal government 
to do something about low livestock and grain prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 900 farmers joined the protest here on the Canadian border  
Friday, while another 120 rallied in Portal, N.D., also on the 
border. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters claim large corporations have created monopolies  
in agribusiness that have depressed prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The rallies were held at the sites of past protests against  
Canadian exports. Farm groups contend Canada has been dumping 
illegally subsidized agricultural products into the United States 
and forcing prices down. 
</P>
<P>
	Dena Hoff, a Montana rancher and chairwoman of the Family Farm  
Coalition's' trade task force, said the protesters don't blame 
Canadian farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won't let agribusiness divide farmers to make us forget  
that corporate manipulation destroys the family farm economy in 
both countries,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several speakers accused the Justice Department of failing to  
attack what they say is unfair competition in their markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a grain cartel out there is what we've got, and it's  
hard for individual farmers to sell into that kind of a market,'' 
said farmer Helen Waller. 
</P>
</TEXT>
