<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gay, Minority Journalists Seek Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Leaders of a national gay and lesbian journalists  
group have proposed stronger ties with the country's largest 
association of minority journalists, saying the move would help 
secure fairer news coverage for all minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Friday, leaders of the National Lesbian and  
Gay Journalists Association asked that Unity: Journalists of Color 
Inc. agree to several proposals, including joint efforts to promote 
accurate coverage of minorities and to fight workplace bias based 
on color, gender or sexual orientation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all going toward the same cause and that's to change the  
hearts and minds of the decision makers of this industry,'' said 
Leroy Aarons, founder of the gay journalists group. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Unity board will take up the proposal in the fall,''  
Catalina Camia, Unity president, said Friday night. ``We felt it 
was not fair of NLGJA to take up the issue in the middle of the 
Unity convention. We're all very busy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 6,000 minority journalists have been meeting here this  
week for the Unity '99 convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Unity includes the Asian American Journalists Association, the  
Native American Journalists Association, the National Association 
of Black Journalists and the National Association of Hispanic 
Journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Unity incorporated under the ``Journalists of Color''  
name. The gay journalists group said in a statement that Unity's 
name change discouraged ``hopes that the organization and NLGJA 
might ever merge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karen Louise Boothe, president of the gay journalists, estimated  
about eight percent of gay and lesbian journalists are also 
minorities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
