<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fusion 2, Crew 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Henry Gutierrez set up one goal and  
scored another on a penalty kick as the Miami Fusion won 
back-to-back games for only the second time this year by beating 
the Columbus Crew 2-0 Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Diego Serna scored in the 31st minute and Gutierrez converted  
his penalty kick in the 85th minute as the Fusion (6-12) moved past 
Tampa Bay into fourth place in Major League Soccer's Eastern 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbus (11-7) lost its second straight game and was shut out  
for the fourth time this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez set a Fusion record with an assist in his fourth  
consecutive game, setting up Serna's 10th goal of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The midfielder's pass to the top of the penalty area found  
Tyrone Marshall, who beat his defender to the corner of the box. 
Marshall crossed to Serna, who one-timed a shot past goalkeeper 
Mark Dougherty. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez scored his fourth goal of the season with the penalty  
kick, coming after Ansil Elcock dragged down Welton in the penalty 
area. That gave Gutierrez 11 points in his last five games. 
</P>
<P>
	Garth Lagerwey made six saves to win his second consecutive  
start in place of the injured Jeff Cassar, who had minor knee 
surgery Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lagerwey's best stop came in the 65th minute when Robert  
Warzycha's free kick from just outside the penalty area curled 
around the wall, off Lagerwey's outstretched arms and off the post. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crew's best scoring chances came early. Stern John shot just  
wide of the net from 15 yards out in the 15th minute. A few minutes 
later, John sent a backheel to Todd Yeagley, whose shot hit the 
crossbar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fusion also had more chances, but failed to capitalize on  
two excellent opportunities in the closing minutes of the first 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 42nd minute, Serna took a pass from Welton and easily  
dribbled around Dougherty to slot a dribbler toward the net. But 
Elcock raced back to clear the ball just as it approached the goal 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than a minute later, Marshall had only Dougherty to beat  
from 10 yards out, but his shot sailed right of the post. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
