<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Discuss China Bomb Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is sending  
officials to Beijing to discuss payments for 20 people injured and 
families of three killed in the mistaken U.S. bombing of the 
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department said Saturday that Undersecretary of State  
Thomas Pickering ``conveyed our willingness to provide a 
humanitarian payment'' when he visited Beijing last month to 
apologize for the ``awful tragedy'' of the May 7 bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Department legal adviser David Andrews will head the delegation  
going to the Chinese capital this coming week, the department said. 
In addition to following up on the offer of payments, it said in a 
statement, Andrews' group will ``discuss issues related to property 
damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration contends a series of errors, including  
erroneous CIA maps pinpointing the embassy as a Yugoslav government 
building, led to the mistaken attack during NATO's air campaign to 
drive Yugoslav forces out of the Serbian province of Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
