<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Slaying Suspects Eyed in Arsons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDDING, Calif. (AP) -- The investigation into arson fires at  
three Sacramento-area synagogues is focusing on two brothers 
suspected in the slayings of a gay couple, a sheriff's official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin Matthew Williams, 31, and James Tyler Williams, 29,  
were arraigned Friday on charges of receiving stolen property, 
which prosecutors said was linked to the killings of Gary Matson 
and Winfield Scott Mowder. 
</P>
<P>
	Literature espousing white supremacist beliefs was found by  
deputies at the brothers' home outside Redding in northern 
California, said Shasta County sheriff's Capt. Ron Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	Matson, 50, and Mowder, 40, were found shot in their bed July 1  
in their Happy Valley home about 180 miles north of San Francisco. 
Richardson said the department hopes to file murder charges against 
the brothers next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said Friday that two men possibly connected to the  
synagogue fires had been arrested by Shasta deputies. It did not 
identify the men. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Friday, the sheriff's department issued a statement saying  
the Williams brothers were ``the two individuals that the FBI in 
Sacramento are focusing on in their investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FBI spokesman Nick Rossi declined to confirm the connection  
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sacramento Bee reported today that the Williamses' arrest  
led officials to discover a list of 32 names linking the siblings 
to the synagogue fires. 
</P>
<P>
	James Maddock, head of the FBI's Sacramento office, had said in  
the earlier FBI statement that the unidentified men had access to 
``substantial armament and ammunition'' and kept a list of names of 
people associated with the synagogues. 
</P>
<P>
	``At present we don't know the purpose of collecting these names  
but obviously we are concerned about their safety and the public 
safety,'' he said. ``We have no evidence of any specific plan of 
any violent action against any specific individual or group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maddock declined to say whether the men would be charged in the  
arsons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those arrests led to additional searches which were monitored  
by this task force,'' Maddock said. ``Those searches yielded 
evidence of potential involvement in or knowledge of the arsons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fires, set within minutes of each other early June 18,  
caused more than $1 million in damage at the Congregation B'nai 
Israel near downtown Sacramento, the Congregation Beth Shalom in 
suburban Carmichael and the Knesset Israel Torah Center in 
northeastern Sacramento County. 
</P>
<P>
	A leaflet blaming the ``International Jew World Order'' for the  
war in Kosovo was left behind at one of the synagogues. 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean and founder of the Simon Wiesenthal  
Center in Los Angeles, called the list of names an ominous 
discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``That follows a pattern of the original haters of the 20th  
century,'' he said. ``When the Nazis came to power, they took with 
them lists of names and addresses of key personnel of various 
synagogues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are examining whether the case is part of a wide  
hate-crime conspiracy and whether the Williams brothers were linked 
to the anti-Semitic World Church of the Creator, based in East 
Peoria, Ill., the Bee reported. 
</P>
<P>
	A former World Church member killed himself last weekend after  
targeting minorities in a shooting spree in Indiana and Illinois 
that left two dead and nine wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the gay couple and the Williams brothers knew each  
other, apparently crossing paths through horticulture. 
</P>
<P>
	``The brothers were in the landscape business and one of the  
victims worked in a nursery at a big store and the other was a 
horticulturist at a local arboretum,'' Richardson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
