<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Famous N.C. Lighthouse Relocated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUXTON, N.C. (AP) -- To the cheers of hundreds of tourists and  
the relief of those who have lived in its long shadow, the Cape 
Hatteras Lighthouse was gently nudged over the threshold of its new 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's tallest brick lighthouse arrived at its new  
concrete foundation Friday afternoon after months of preparation 
work and a three-week journey that covered almost 2,900 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	The 208-foot-tall tower, which was just 150 feet from the  
crashing Atlantic surf a few weeks ago, is now 1,600 feet from the 
ocean's edge -- the same distance from that shoreline that it was 
when built 129 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	National Park Service officials say the black-and-white striped  
tower should be safe from erosion for at least a century. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some that will say we've destroyed history,'' said  
Park Service spokesman Bob Woody, referring to those who opposed 
the move and advocated groins to protect the lighthouse at its 
original location. ``The people who will visit this lighthouse 100 
years from now will give us the answer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lighthouse began its journey on June 17, resting on a nest  
of steel beams mounted on rollers as it was pushed along rails by 
seven hydraulic jacks. Originally expected to take four to six 
weeks, the $10 million move took three. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Matyiko of Expert House Movers of Virginia Beach, Va., the  
moving subcontractor, exchanged high fives and handshakes with 
surveyor John Mayne when the tower came to a stop Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Park Service later tested the lighthouse's twin beams, which  
were extinguished March 1 for the first time in 50 years. They are 
scheduled to be lighted on Labor Day, and officials plan to reopen 
the lighthouse to visitors next Memorial Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Ryan, a ranger with the Cape Hatteras National Seashore,  
jokingly gave the movers phony tickets for failure to stop and for 
exceeding speed for a lighthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the first time I've enjoyed getting a ticket,'' said Joe  
Jakubik, project manager for general contractor International 
Chimney Co. of Buffalo, N.Y. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
