<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Come back next week to play the Des  
Moines Golf and Country Club and you'll get an extra stroke at hole 
No. 5. There are no such luxuries for the U.S. Senior Open. 
</P>
<P>
	The fifth is a 445-yard par-5 for club members on a par-73  
course. It was changed to a par-4 for the Senior Open, but no 
changes were made to the hole's layout. 
</P>
<P>
	Golfers have to hit their drives over a rise, and from there the  
fairway slopes uphill and to the left. Most golfers have had to 
play their second shot over a grove of ash trees, usually from 
about 160 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously they didn't want a par-73 on the golf course, but,  
yeah, those trees are always going to bother you,'' said Frank 
Conner, who made par at No. 5 on Friday and Saturday after a double 
bogey in the first round. ``I was in the right cut and where they 
put the pin (Saturday) was back left. The trees were in my way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hole cost leader Ed Dougherty a double-bogey Saturday, but  
defending champion Hale Irwin birdied it. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *COOPERATING CONDITIONS:* Some golfers who barely made the  
weekend cut -- a two-day total of 150 -- were able to get at least 
within striking distance Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Colbert and Conner both teed off in the afternoon Thursday,  
battling steamy temperatures in the 90s and beat-up greens. Colbert 
shot an 8-over 80, and Conner was 7-over. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thursday, I wasted nine shots on the greens or around them,''  
Colbert said. ``It was by far the toughest day to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Colbert was at 148 and Conner at 150.  
</P>
<P>
	Conner shot a tournament-best 67 Saturday and went into Sunday's  
round at 1-over 217. Colbert drew to even-par with a 68. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, there was a big advantage on the greens,'' Conner  
said. ``The greens are in perfect shape when we played. I played 
obviously better today than I have in the last couple of days. But 
really, I felt like I played pretty much good all week, even though 
I shot 79, I just putted horribly.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE WAITING GAME:* Before the first players teed off Saturday,  
Sandra Roberts and Cathy Courtney were in place at the 18th green. 
</P>
<P>
	The cousins picked out choice, front-row seats in the bleachers  
at 8 a.m. and prepared to wait four hours for the first golfers to 
arrive. At 9:30, they were among a handful of people in the stands, 
and most of those folks were at the top of the bleachers, where 
they could see the first tee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've done the walk-around thing, I've kind of done it all, and  
this is how I wanted to do it today,'' said Courtney, who is from 
Knoxville, about 30 miles southeast of Des Moines. 
</P>
<P>
	She took the week off work to come to the Senior Open every day,  
and she staked out the first tee at 7 a.m. Thursday to see Arnold 
Palmer's 12:50 p.m. tee-off. 
</P>
<P>
	The galleries along the first fairway early Saturday were four  
to five people deep. At the first hole, the crowd was 10-deep in 
places. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ROUGHRIDING:* The Senior Open is leaving a lasting impression  
on the Des Moines Golf and Country Club -- especially its roads and 
parking lots. 
</P>
<P>
	Convoys of city buses shuttling spectators from outlying parking  
lots are tearing up the asphalt. A dump truck arrived Saturday 
morning with a load of gravel and added it to a 6-foot pile in what 
will again be the country club members' parking lot on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Tuesday, crews have come out nightly to repair several  
torn-up patches. The largest stretches the width of the road and is 
about 20 yards long. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Mason, the USGA's championship director, said the  
organization will pay the Des Moines Golf and Country Club for 
repairs. He said temperatures in the 90s early in the week, 
combined with the weight of the buses, are to blame. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ATTENDANCE:* Saturday's attendance was 47,200. It was the sixth  
straight day, including the practice rounds, the crowds have 
increased. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never witnessed those numbers,'' said Craig Smith, the  
tournament's media relations manager and a USGA employee since 
1989. ``When they told me, I said, `Are you sure?' It's pretty 
incredible.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
