<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pete Conrad To Be Buried With Honors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Apollo 12 astronaut Pete Conrad, the  
third man to walk on the moon, will be buried with full military 
honors in Arlington National Cemetery on July 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Conrad was killed in a motorcycle accident Thursday in Southern  
California. He was 69. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Apollo astronauts plan to attend the graveside service,  
said Howard Benedict, executive director of the Astronaut 
Scholarship Foundation near Cape Canaveral. Details are still being 
worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members and close friends will gather Sunday at the  
Conrad home in Huntington Beach, Calif., said Benedict. The 
astronaut is survived by his wife, Nancy, three sons and seven 
grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Conrad, a former Navy captain, flew in space four times: twice  
during the Gemini program in the mid-1960s, as commander of Apollo 
12 in November 1969, and as commander of NASA's Skylab space 
station in 1973. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 04:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elton John Given Pacemaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Elton John has had a pacemaker inserted to  
overcome what he called ``a minor imbalance in my heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaving London's Wellington Hospital today, the 52-year-old pop  
star told reporters, ``I feel very well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a bit stiff, a bit sore but everything went really well,''  
he said before driving off in a chauffeured limousine. 
</P>
<P>
	``It came as a bit of a shock, but the operation was a simple  
procedure, the only thing I really regret is canceling my shows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had thought he was suffering from sunstroke after  
playing tennis at his house in Nice, France. He took ill on a 
flight to Ireland where he was to have performed at the July 4 
wedding of singer Victoria Adams, known as Posh Spice, and soccer 
player David Beckham. 
</P>
<P>
	``Literally, I was on the plane to David and Victoria's wedding,  
but I was ill and had to have some tests. I was given the all-clear 
and went back to France,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He had continued to feel weak so came to London for tests, he  
said. He was admitted to the hospital Friday and had the pacemaker 
put in the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will resume a normal lifestyle after a couple of months  
rest. Life will get back to normal,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his fans had been very supportive, and he promised that  
every canceled show would be rescheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	He also issued a statement saying the only long-term effect of  
the heart problem ``is that I have to carry a card explaining why I 
set off the alarms when I walk through airport security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pacemakers regulate the heartbeat by sending an electrical  
charge from a tiny lithium battery down a wire to the heart muscle. 
They are usually placed in a pocket under the skin of the abdomen 
or the collarbone. 
</P>
<P>
	Sir Elton called his pacemaker a precaution against further  
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the first the problem was diagnosed as a viral problem in  
the middle ear, but after a long series of tests it was also 
discovered that there was a minor imbalance in my heart,'' his 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a short and commonplace procedure,'' it said. ``I  
stayed in hospital overnight just for observation and I have now 
been discharged and later today I will be returning to Nice to 
recover and rest. 
</P>
<P>
	``My doctors have ordered me to rest for the rest of the month  
and I will not therefore be able to play at any of the concerts 
planned this month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had canceled three concerts scheduled for today, Sunday and  
Monday in southern England, and hours before the operation he 
announced he was pulling out of two concerts in northern England 
next weekend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 10:58:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India Clears Key Sector in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- After two months of heavy ground  
fighting, Indian forces say they pushed Pakistan-based Islamic 
guerrillas back across the cease-fire line in a key battle zone in 
Kashmir, but suffered heavy losses in another sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Fierce fighting raged Friday night and this morning in Mushkoh  
Valley, where India lost 48 soldiers in two days -- even as Pakistan 
was asking Muslim insurgents to help ``resolve the crisis'' in an 
apparent call to withdraw. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time India claimed to have reached the  
cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's now only a matter of a few days before the last of the  
Pakistani intruders are flushed out -- dead or alive,'' India's 
Defense Minister George Fernandes said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian troops cleared most guerrillas from Batalik, the  
easternmost of four battle sectors in the Himalayan mountains of 
Kashmir, and from a second sector, Dras, military spokesman Col. 
Bikram Singh said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian claims of spectacular victories in Batalik -- capturing  
eight mountaintop positions in less than 24 hours without losing a 
soldier-- came as the Pakistani Cabinet's defense committee was 
meeting in Islamabad to ask insurgents for help resolving the 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether the rebels retreated from Batalik in  
response to political and diplomatic efforts, or whether their 
positions crumbled under the pressure of Indian fire. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, top Pakistani commanders met the leaders of 11  
militant groups fighting in Kashmir to discuss a withdrawal, a 
government official said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif is expected to brief his  
Cabinet today on his visit to Washington, where he promised 
President Clinton he would take ``concrete steps'' to end the 
fighting. He is scheduled to make a statement in parliament Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mushkoh Valley, thousands of Indian paratroop commandos who  
specialize in high-altitude warfare milled about an army base 
today. An atmosphere of gloom prevailed as 79 wounded soldiers were 
brought down the mountains on horses, stretchers and helicopters 
Friday and today. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them, Narendra Singh, hobbled down a snowcapped hill for  
five hours, supported by two soldiers, before he reached a field 
medical unit with a doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I climbed on a boulder and shot three people. Suddenly 10 to  
12 people emerged from behind a rock and fired a machine gun at us. 
I jumped down 20 feet and was badly hurt,'' Singh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers said they saw shell-proof bunkers on the top of the  
mountains. One covered in aluminum sheets decorated with a crescent 
was used as a mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	India says Pakistani troops are leading 700 to 800 fighters in  
Kashmir, a border region divided between the two countries and 
claimed in its entirety by both. 
</P>
<P>
	But Islamabad says the fighters are Kashmiri insurgents who  
receive only moral support from Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Singh said 639 Pakistani soldiers and more than 150 Islamic  
guerrillas have been killed in the fighting since early May, while 
321 Indian soldiers have died, 451 were wounded and 10 were 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pakistan, religious groups rallied in major cities Friday  
against Sharif's pledge to withdraw the militants fighting Indian 
troops in Kashmir, shouting ``Down with Nawaz Sharif'' and 
``Traitor Nawaz Sharif.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
