<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 01:00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Copper Demand Spurs Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Larry Nelson is sure he'll never find another job  
paying him nearly $18 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Until last month, he was earning the wage as a pipe fitter at  
the Broken Hill Property Co.'s sprawling copper mining, smelter and 
refining operation in San Manuel, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Nelson, a 25-year company employee, is among its 2,200  
laid-off workers scrambling for new work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm adjusting to the fact that I'll be making less money than  
before,'' said Nelson, 48, president of the local United 
Steelworkers of America chapter. 
</P>
<P>
	Depressed demand and prices have recently caused producers in  
Arizona, New Mexico, Nevada and Texas to shut down entire 
operations and scale back production. 
</P>
<P>
	Since June, three major copper producers have announced layoffs.  
Broken Hill is shutting down operations in San Manuel and Nevada; 
Phelps Dodge Corp. is laying off 1,650 workers in Arizona, New 
Mexico and Texas; and Asarco Inc. is cutting 150 people in Arizona 
-- a 17 percent reduction. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona, previously home to 12 active copper mines, produces  
two-thirds of U.S.-mined copper. But the 4,000 lost jobs have cast 
uncertainty on the mineral's fate in the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Jobs cut at Ascarco and Phelps Dodge, for instance, could return  
if demand increases and the industry returns ``to a little 
normalcy,'' said Marshall Vest, a specialist at the University of 
Arizona's Division of Economic and Business Research. Yet the jobs 
at Broken Hill would be costly to bring back, even if another 
producer takes it over, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's expensive to shut a plant down, and even more expensive  
to reopen it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper prices slid from $1.18 a pound in 1996 to an average of  
65 cents this year, partly because of overproduction and a slowdown 
in construction demand in the shrunken economies of Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs are part of a strategy to lower production in hopes  
of increasing prices, said George Leaming, an Arizona mining 
economist. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuts appear to be helping somewhat, he said. Reduced production  
is boosting copper prices to around 75 cents a pound, last year's 
average. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the price coming back up, the producers can make a little  
money,'' Leaming said. ``It's not the death of the industry by any 
means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the layoffs and reduced production will be a  
drag on the Arizona economy. The state could lose up to $35 million 
in tax revenue alone, Leaming said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks aren't unilateral. Copper producer Cyprus-Climax  
Metals, which employs 2,000 at two mines and a smelter, has said it 
plans no layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it remains an uncertain time for industry workers.  
</P>
<P>
	``All these corporations have mines all over the America, and  
these mines have the highest costs,'' said Ian Robertson, president 
of the Southern Arizona Labor Council and an Asarco employee. 
``It's cheaper for them to keep a mine open in Chile.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 10:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Bankers Say Reform Slipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Although Asia has started to recover from its  
economic crisis, the pace of financial reform is slipping, central 
bankers said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a meeting with executives from the Bank for International  
Settlements, or BIS, Asian central bankers raised concerns about 
the way reform in the international financial system is proceeding, 
Andrew Crockett, general manager of the BIS, told reporters after 
the closed-door meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Basel, Switzerland-based BIS is regarded as the central  
banker for central banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian stock markets have rallied in recent weeks, though some  
analysts wonder whether traders have overestimated the actual 
prospects for a recovery. Some blue chip indexes have soared to 
levels unseen since before the Asian crisis spread in the autumn of 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankers also said they want a larger role in the BIS'  
Financial Stability Forum, an organization of central banks and 
regulatory agencies led by the Group of Seven countries and headed 
by Crockett. 
</P>
<P>
	Crockett said he would raise the bankers' concerns at future  
forum meetings. But he stopped short of promising broader 
participation by Asia's smaller economies, noting that Hong Kong 
and Singapore have been invited to participate because of the size 
and importance of their financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of the 11 top central bankers from the region were  
concerned with the BIS proposal for changing bank lending 
guidelines. They were worried that the new system would rely too 
much on the views of credit ratings agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Crockett and other BIS member bankers are to convene their next  
meeting Monday in Shanghai where he expects further discussion on 
the stability forum. The region's economies and banking reforms 
will also be discussed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In their Friday meeting, the region's bankers stressed that  
reforms are still needed to ensure a sustained return to financial 
health. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian monetary bosses came from Australia, China, Hong Kong,  
Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, New Zealand, the Philippines, 
Singapore, South Korea and Thailand. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
