<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 00:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Market To Compete With Nasdaq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Scrambling to meet a challenge by the operator of  
the Nasdaq Stock Market, Japan's largest stock exchange will also 
set up a new market for smaller start-up companies, a newspaper 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Stock Exchange will open the new market early next  
year with relaxed listing requirements to attract smaller, lesser 
known companies that are now unable to raise money on Japan's 
financial markets, the Nihon Keizai newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was available at the Tokyo Stock Exchange to take calls  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report comes less than a month after the National  
Association of Securities Dealers Inc., which runs the highly 
successful Nasdaq market in the United States, and a Japanese 
software company announced they will open a similar market in Japan 
by the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	No such market currently exists in Japan, a fact many economists  
here blame for the country's failure to keep up with the 
technological innovation going on at companies in places like 
Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq has grown into one of the world's largest stock  
markets largely because of its success in directing investors' 
funds to rapidly growing start-up companies. 
</P>
<P>
	With Japan struggling through its longest recession since World  
War II, economists have called for the establishment of such 
capital markets here to put the bounce back in Asia's largest 
economy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
