<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Contractor May Escape Fines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The Pentagon says it will excuse  
millions of dollars in fines against Lockheed Martin if the defense 
contractor can improve the performance of a new missile system. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin faced $15 million in fines for failing to  
deliver a working defense system on time. But the Pentagon modified 
the company's contract to allow the company more time to fix the 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``The intent was not to penalize them,'' Jennifer Canaff,  
spokeswoman for the Pentagon's Ballistic Missile Defense 
Organization, said Friday. ``The attempt was to gain more 
information and more data on how to make this missile system 
work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Theater High-Altitude Area Defense, or THAAD, missile  
defense system failed in March for the sixth time to intercept a 
flying target missile. 
</P>
<P>
	But company and Pentagon officials said the contract for the  
$3.8 billion system was changed after the fifth failure to allow it 
to escape penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Under those changes, the $15 million penalty for the March  
failure would be waived if it manages three successful intercepts 
by the end of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Ashdown, spokesman for the Washington-based Taxpayers for  
Common Sense, criticized the arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are allowed to fail as long as they get it right in the  
end,'' he said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
