<DOCNO> APW19990710.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 20:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Stays Up to Watch World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- In the end, it was the game.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite its billing as a grudge match between two countries with  
lots of animosity, China's loss to the United States in a grueling 
women's World Cup showdown brought admiration from hardened Chinese 
soccer fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both teams played their best. Finally it came down to luck,''  
said Meng Xianyu, one of 60 soccer enthusiasts packed into the 
smoky Soccer Buff's Cafe. ``The American team just outlasted the 
Chinese team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soccer fans throughout Beijing spent a sleepless night Saturday  
waiting to watch their team take on the Americans in the World Cup 
final, shown live on nationwide television starting at 4 a.m. local 
time Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The outcome -- a loss on penalty kicks after two overtime  
periods-- drew huge cries of disappointment. Americans beat China 
5-4 in the shootout following a 0-0 tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows that match was not fair. That ball went in,''  
said office worker Xu Li, referring to a header by Fan Yunjie. She 
cried when the Chinese lost. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was just too tragic, too tragic,'' said Ma Zhengmei.  
</P>
<P>
	China's state-run media fanned suspicions that referees favored  
the Americans in earlier clashes between the two teams. Newspapers 
worried that the Chinese team was weak, unable to find real Chinese 
food and having been made to crisscross the United States in 
earlier rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. arranged it this way for the final battle,'' said  
Wang, the businessman. ``We feel we haven't gotten enough respect'' 
from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In anticipation of possible trouble, a busload of 30 police  
waited by the side of the U.S. Embassy, which was stoned by tens of 
thousands of Chinese for four days after the May 7 bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Heightened emotions in China's capital, however, were mainly  
channeled toward the game. On the contest's eve, the Beijing Youth 
Daily reported that more than nine out of 10 people in the 116 
households it surveyed said they would watch the game live, despite 
the hour. 
</P>
<P>
	The game's late hour meant news of the loss did not make it into  
Sunday newspapers. But state television broadcast the results 
repeatedly. National dailies printed a brief account of President 
Jiang Zemin's telephoned encouragement to the Chinese team. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have demonstrated fully the aspiration to win honors for  
the motherland,'' Jiang said in comments carried by the official 
Xinhua News Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether you win or lose, the whole nation and the people will  
extend their warmest greetings to you,'' Jiang added. 
</P>
<P>
	A refined appreciation for the game and the importance of the  
moment prevailed at the Soccer Buff's Cafe. Many fans debated the 
strengths of the opposing teams: the Americans had the physical 
strength while the Chinese had experience and teamwork. 
</P>
<P>
	The tiny Sichuan restaurant in a working-class south Beijing  
neighborhood was festooned with balloons, red for Chinese national 
team and green for Beijing's top men's soccer club, Guo'an. 
Cigarette-filled ashtrays, watermelon rinds and beer bottles 
littered the tables. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a normal thing to lose on penalty kicks. Even Italy's  
greatest star Baggio missed a penalty kick in a World Cup. That's 
not so bad,'' said Wang Zhanjun, an unemployed factory worker and 
frequent present at the cafe. ``It's an honor for the Chinese 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the men's team has never qualified for a World Cup,  
soccer in China has largely been viewed as a male sport. The 
success of the women's team is helping win them some long overdue 
recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	``In our dorm, we only have posters of male soccer players.  
There aren't any posters or photos of women soccer stars,'' Ren 
Liping, a 21-year-old member of the Beijing women's soccer team, 
said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This might change that. Now, maybe someone will take pictures  
of us,'' teammate Luo Ting said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990710.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 08:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
