<DOCNO> APW19990710.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Preventative Medicare  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton today said preventive  
medical care must be made affordable to older Americans who rely on 
Medicare. ``No senior should have to hesitate to get the preventive 
care they need,'' the president said in his weekly radio address. 
Under his proposal, co-payments and deductibles for preventive 
medical care such as hepatitis B vaccinations, colo-rectal and 
prostate cancer screening and diabetes management, would be 
eliminated for Medicare beneficiaries. 

</P>
<P>
	Neo-Nazis March in Idaho  
</P>
<P>
	COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) -- Under the protection of a federal  
court order, members of the Aryan Nations today paraded through 
downtown streets. But they were outshouted by protesters who forced 
the marchers to detour. Four protesters were arrested. After the 
20-minute parade, some of the two dozen Aryans saluted supporters 
in the crowd with the Nazi straight-arm gesture. City officials had 
urged people to ignore the march, but thousands of opponents 
gathered along the parade route, chanting ``No Nazis! No KKK! No 
fascists! USA!'' 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen Warns Yugoslav Troops  
</P>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Acknowledging slow progress in deploying  
allied peacekeepers in Kosovo, Defense Secretary William Cohen said 
today that NATO has plans to respond with force if Serbs resist. 
Amid growing signs of tension between Serbia and Montenegro and 
daily outbreaks of violence in Kosovo, the arriving Kosovo 
peacekeeping force, or KFOR, is prepared for trouble. ``We have 
contingency plans in the event there were any action taken by 
Milosevic against KFOR,'' Cohen said after talks with Nordic and 
Baltic defense ministers. He rated the risk of trouble as unlikely. 

</P>
<P>
	Flooding Wreaks Havoc in Serbia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Overnight storms wreaked havoc with  
railway and road traffic throughout Serbia. Flooding forced some to 
flee their homes and left parts Belgrade, the capital, without 
power or drinking water. At least one death was reported and 10 
people are missing. ``This must be a punishment from God. First 
NATO nearly destroyed everything I had, then this,'' said Petko 
Budimir, whose house was flooded. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA Testing New Air Traffic System  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) -- The future of air traffic control got a  
flight test today as more than a dozen planes with 
satellite-positioning systems flew over Ohio and Kentucky while 
monitors tracked the exact location of each aircraft. The ``ADS-B'' 
system, more accurate than radar and with a longer range than 
existing collision-avoidance systems, simultaneously gives air 
traffic controllers and pilots an instant look at where the 
airplanes were and whether any were on conflicting courses. 

</P>
<P>
	Fla. Police Chief's Sons Charged  
</P>
<P>
	HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) -- Two police officers -- both sons of the  
local police chief -- face brutality charges over the beating of a 
man they arrested and allegedly took in handcuffs to a remote 
parking lot. The patrolmen, Daniel Bolanos and Rolando Bolanos Jr., 
surrendered yesterday. They are accused of beating Yoel Pacheco in 
November after taking him to the lot near the Hialeah Park 
racetrack, and then trying to cover it up with false police 
reports. 

</P>
<P>
	Indian Jets Pound Guerrilla Areas  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Indian fighter planes pounded  
guerrilla positions in a Himalayan battle zone today amid 
government claims that rebels in some areas have been pushed back 
across the cease-fire line dividing Kashmir. Pilots flying 
French-built Mirages and Russian-made MiGs dropped as much as 15 
tons of explosives on Pakistan-backed rebel positions, an Air Force 
spokesman said. Kashmir, a border region divided between the two 
countries, is claimed in its entirety by both India and Pakistan. 

</P>
<P>
	Protestant Rally in Belfast OK'd  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Facing threats of a standoff by  
Northern Ireland's major Protestant brotherhood, authorities today 
said they would allow the group to hold a mass demonstration near 
hostile Catholic turf. The Northern Ireland Parades Commission's 
decision to lift its earlier ban came after leaders of the Orange 
Order protested, raising the possibility of an ugly standoff 
between the group and police. The demonstration is scheduled for 
Monday. The Orangemen stage marches across Northern Ireland on July 
12 to commemorate a 1690 Protestant victory over Catholics. 

</P>
<P>
	Soccer: U.S. Women Play China  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The U.S. soccer team is playing China  
today in the women's World Cup title game. A sell-out crowd of 
about 90,000 fans, including President Clinton, was expected. China 
won two of three meetings this season. The game was to be televised 
live in China. 

</P>
<P>
